# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: african-americans
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:african-americans/125th-street-manhattan] Notable buildings along 125th Street include the Apollo Theater, the Adam Clayton Powell Jr.
[src:african-americans/125th-street-manhattan] State Office Building, the Hotel Theresa, the Studio Museum in Harlem, the Mount Morris Bank Building, Harlem Commonwealth Council, the Harlem Children's Zone, the Church of St.
[src:african-americans/125th-street-manhattan] Joseph of the Holy Family, and the former West End Theatre, now home to the La Gree Baptist Church.
[src:african-americans/125th-street-manhattan] The street was designated by the Commissioners' Plan of 1811 that established the Manhattan street grid as one of 15 east–west streets that would be 100 feet (30 m) in width (while other streets were designated as 60 feet (18 m) in width).
[src:african-americans/125th-street-manhattan] The western part of the street runs diagonally between the neighborhoods of Manhattanville and Morningside Heights from the northwest from the West Harlem Piers and an interchange with the Henry Hudson Parkway at 130th Street.
[src:african-americans/125th-street-manhattan] East of Morningside Avenue it runs east–west through central Harlem to Second Avenue, where a ramp connects it to the Robert F.
[src:african-americans/125th-street-manhattan] However, 125th Street continues to First Avenue, where it connects to the southbound FDR Drive and the Willis Avenue Bridge.
[src:african-americans/125th-street-manhattan] West of Convent Avenue, 125th Street was rerouted onto what was, prior to 1920, called Manhattan Street.
[src:african-americans/125th-street-manhattan] What remains of the original alignment of 125th Street was renamed La Salle Street at that time.
[src:african-americans/125th-street-manhattan] The remaining blocks run between Amsterdam Avenue and Claremont Avenue.
[src:african-americans/125th-street-manhattan] *The New York Times* lamented the name changes, noting that the new names had "somewhat doubtful nomenclature", and that the City's "Aldermen like French names" but gave no rationale for the moves otherwise.
[src:african-americans/125th-street-manhattan] A block of the original 125th Street in this area was de-mapped to make the super-blocks where the Grant Houses projects now exist.
[src:african-americans/125th-street-manhattan] A proposal to convert the street into a Trans-Harlem Expressway died when funds were diverted from the proposed 125th Street Hudson River bridge at the street's western end.
[src:african-americans/125th-street-manhattan] Beginning in the late 1990s, many sections of 125th Street have been gentrified and developed with such stores as MAC Cosmetics, Old Navy, H&M, CVS/pharmacy, and Magic Johnson Theaters.
[src:african-americans/125th-street-manhattan] In collaboration with the community, the city has developed a plan for the 125th Street corridor focusing on reinforcing and building upon its strengths as an arts and cultural corridor.
[src:african-americans/125th-street-manhattan] A rift in the crust runs along underneath this street from the East River to New Jersey and is known as the **125th Street Fault** or the **Manhattanville Fault**.
[src:african-americans/125th-street-manhattan] It is suspected to have caused a magnitude-5.2 earthquake in 1737, two smaller ones in 1981, and a 2.4 magnitude quake in 2001.
[src:african-americans/125th-street-manhattan] The fault line skims across the top of Central Park and runs to Roosevelt Island to the southeast.
[src:african-americans/125th-street-manhattan] It creates a fault valley deep enough to require the IRT Broadway–Seventh Avenue Line (1 train) to use a trestle between 122nd and 135th Streets, even though the line goes underground at either end and remains at the same elevation above sea level throughout.
[src:african-americans/125th-street-manhattan] Riverside Drive also crosses over the fault valley on a high viaduct.
[src:african-americans/125th-street-manhattan] Metro-North Railroad's Harlem–125th Street station is located at the street's intersection with Park Avenue.
[src:african-americans/125th-street-manhattan] The planned second phase of the Second Avenue Subway, continuing north from the 116th Street station, will turn westward onto 125th Street, terminating at a station at Lexington Avenue.
[src:african-americans/125th-street-manhattan] The new station would connect to the Metro-North and preexisting Lexington Avenue subway stations there.
[src:african-americans/1790-united-states-census] The **1790 United States census** was the first United States census.
[src:african-americans/1790-united-states-census] It recorded the population of the whole United States as of Census Day, August 2, 1790, as mandated by Article 1, Section 2, of the Constitution and applicable laws.
[src:african-americans/1790-united-states-census] In the first census, the population of the United States was enumerated to be 3,929,214 inhabitants.
[src:african-americans/1790-united-states-census] Congress assigned responsibility for the 1790 census to the marshals of United States judicial districts under an act, which with minor modifications and extensions, governed census taking through the 1840 census.
[src:african-americans/1790-united-states-census] Both Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson and President George Washington expressed skepticism over the results, believing that the true population had been undercounted.
[src:african-americans/1790-united-states-census] If indeed an undercount was the result, possible explanations for it include dispersed population, poor transportation links, limitations of contemporary technology, and individual refusal to participate.
[src:african-americans/1790-united-states-census] Although the census was proved statistically factual, based on data collected, the records for several states (including Delaware, Georgia, New Jersey, and Virginia) were lost sometime between 1790 and 1830.
[src:african-americans/1790-united-states-census] Almost one-third of the original census data have been lost or destroyed since their original documentation.
[src:african-americans/1790-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1790 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:african-americans/1790-united-states-census] The census was not conducted in Vermont until 1791, after that state's admission to the Union as the 14th state on March 4 of that year.
[src:african-americans/1790-united-states-census] At 17.8 percent, the 1790 census's proportion of slaves to the free population was the highest ever recorded by any census of the United States.
[src:african-americans/1790-united-states-census] 0 is the correct figure, and the 16 here should be added to the "All other free persons" column.
[src:african-americans/1790-united-states-census] When the census of 1790 was published in 1791, it reported 16 slaves, which were illegal in Vermont.
[src:african-americans/1790-united-states-census] Subsequently, and up to 1860, the number is given as 17.
[src:african-americans/1790-united-states-census] An examination of the original manuscript by the Census Bureau superintendent found that there never were any slaves in Vermont.
[src:african-americans/1790-united-states-census] The original error occurred in preparing the results for publication, when 16 persons, returned as "Free colored," were classified as "Slave" in Bennington County.
[src:african-americans/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 85,425, or 114 less than figures published in 1790, due to an error of addition of several towns.
[src:african-americans/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 59,096, or 2 more than figures published in 1790, due to error in addition.
[src:african-americans/1790-united-states-census] The figures for Virginia do not include the population of Kentucky.
[src:african-americans/1790-united-states-census] Though Kentucky was then a part of Virginia, the Kentucky figures were compiled separately, and are shown on the line for Kentucky.
[src:african-americans/1790-united-states-census] The Virginia figures do include the portion of Virginia that later became the state of West Virginia.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] The **2000 United States census**, conducted by the Census Bureau, determined the resident population of the United States on April 1, 2000, to be 281,421,906, an increase of 13.2 percent over the 248,709,873 people enumerated during the 1990 census.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] This was the twenty-second federal census and was at the time the largest civilly administered peacetime effort in the United States.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] Approximately 16 percent of households received a "long form" of the 2000 census, which contained over 100 questions.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] It would be the last census to include the "long form", since subsequent censuses, starting with the 2010 census, would be "short form" only, with the more detailed questions being replaced by the new American Community Survey.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] Full documentation on the 2000 census, including census forms and a procedural history, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a state—California—recorded a population of over 30 million, as well as the first in which two states—California and Texas—recorded populations of more than 20 million.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] Microdata from the 2000 census is freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with electronic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] Personally identifiable information will be available in 2072.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] The U.S. resident population includes the total number of people in the 50 states and the District of Columbia.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] The Bureau also enumerated the residents of the U.S. territory of Puerto Rico; its population was 3,808,610, an 8.1% increase over the number from a decade earlier.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] Regionally, the South and West experienced the bulk of the nation's population increase: 14,790,890 and 10,411,850, respectively.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] This meant that the mean center of U.S. population moved to Phelps County, Missouri.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] The Northeastern United States grew by 2,785,149; the Midwest by 4,724,144.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] The results of the census are used to determine how many congressional districts each state is apportioned.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] Congress defines the formula, in accordance with Title 2 of the U.S.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] Code, to reapportion among the states the 435 seats in the United States House of Representatives.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] The apportionment population consists of the resident population of the fifty states, plus the overseas military and federal civilian employees and their dependents living with them who could be allocated to a state.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] Each member of the House represents a population of about 647,000.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] The populations of the District of Columbia and Puerto Rico are excluded from the apportionment population because they do not have voting seats in the U.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] Since the first census in 1790, the decennial count has been the basis for the United States representative form of government.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] Article I, Section II specifies that "The Number of Representatives shall not exceed one for every thirty Thousand, but each State shall have at Least one Representative." In 1790, each member of the House represented about 34,000 residents.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] Since then, the House more than quadrupled in size, and in 1911 the number of representatives was fixed at 435.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] Today, each member represents about 20 times as many constituents.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] In the years leading up to the 2000 census, there was substantial controversy over whether the Bureau should adjust census figures based on a follow-up survey, called the post-enumeration survey, of a sample of blocks.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] This recommendation was followed by the Secretary of Commerce (the official in charge of making the determination).
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] After the census was tabulated, Utah challenged the results in two different ways.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] Utah was extremely close to gaining a fourth congressional seat, falling 857 people short, which in turn was allocated to North Carolina.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] The margin was later shortened to 80 people, after the federal government discovered that it overcounted the population of North Carolina by 2,673 residents.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] The Census Bureau counted members of the military and other federal civilian employees serving abroad as residents of their home state but did not count other people living outside the United States.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] Utah claimed that people traveling abroad as religious missionaries should be counted as residents and that the failure to do so imposed a burden on Mormon religious practice.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] Almost half of all Mormon missionaries, more than 11,000 people, were from Utah; only 102 came from North Carolina.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] If this policy were changed, then Utah would have received an additional seat instead of North Carolina.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] On November 26, 2002, the Supreme Court affirmed the lower court ruling that rejected Utah's efforts to have Mormon missionaries counted.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] The state of Utah then filed another lawsuit alleging that the statistical methods used in computing the state populations were improper and cost Utah the seat.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] The Bureau uses a method called imputation to assign a number of residents to addresses where residents cannot be reached after multiple efforts.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] While nationwide the imputation method added 0.4% to the population, the rate in Utah was 0.2%.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] The state challenged that the use of imputation violates the Census Act of 1957 and that it also fails the Constitution's requirement in Article I, Section 2 that an "actual enumeration" be used for apportionment.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] Evans*, made it to the Supreme Court, but Utah was again defeated.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] The census forms did not include any questions regarding sexual orientation, making it impossible to compile data comparing heterosexual and homosexual populations.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] However, two questions *were* asked that allowed same-sex partnerships to be counted.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] The questionnaires asked the sex of each person in a household and they asked what the relationship was between each of the members of the household.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] Respondents could check "Husband/wife" or "unmarried partner" or a number of other relationships.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] Responses were tabulated and the Census Bureau reported that there were more than 658,000 same-sex couples heading households in the United States.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] However, only about 25% of gay men and 40% of lesbians are in shared-household partnerships at any one time, according to non-census surveys.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] For every same-sex couple tallied in the census, there could be three to six more homosexual un-partnered individuals who would not be counted as gay.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] The census reported that same-sex male couples numbered 336,001 and female same-sex couples numbered 329,522.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] Extrapolating from those figures and the surveyed partnering habits of homosexuals, as many as 4.3 million homosexual adults could have been living in the U.S. in 2000.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] The exact number cannot be known because the census did not count them specifically.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] Bisexual and transgender populations were not counted, either, because there were no questions regarding this information.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] Also unavailable is the number of additional same-sex couples living under the same roof as the first, though this applies to additional heterosexual couples as well.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] The lack of accurate numbers makes it difficult for lawmakers who are considering legislation on hate crimes or social services for gay families with children.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] It also makes for less accuracy when predicting the fertility of a population.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] Another issue that concerned gay rights advocates involved the automatic changing of data during the tabulation process.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] This automatic software data compiling method, called *allocation*, was designed to counteract mistakes and discrepancies in returned questionnaires.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] Forms that were filled out by two same-sex persons who checked the "Husband/wife" relationship box were treated as a discrepancy.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] The Census Bureau explained that same-sex "Husband/wife" data samples were changed to "unmarried partner" by computer processing methods in 99% of the cases.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] In the remaining 1%, computer systems used one of two possibilities: a) one of the two listed sexes was changed, making the partnership appear heterosexual, or b) if the two partners were more than 15 years apart in age, they might have been reassigned into a familial parent/child relationship.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] The process of automatic reassignment of same-sex marriage data was initiated so that the Census Bureau would not contravene the Defense of Marriage Act passed in 1996.
[src:african-americans/2000-united-states-census] With allocation moving married same-sex couples to the unmarried partner category, social scientists lost information that could have been extracted relating to the social stability of a same-gender couple who identify themselves as married.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 4, 2008.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Democratic ticket of Illinois junior senator Barack Obama and Delaware senior senator Joe Biden, defeated the Republican ticket of Arizona senior senator John McCain and Alaska governor Sarah Palin.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Obama became the first African American to be elected to the presidency.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Incumbent Republican president George W.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush was ineligible to pursue a third term due to the term limits established by the Twenty-second Amendment; this was the first election since 1952 in which neither the incumbent president nor vice president was on the ballot, and the first since 1928 in which neither ran for the nomination.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McCain secured the Republican nomination by March 2008, defeating his main challengers Mitt Romney and Mike Huckabee, and selected Palin as his running mate.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Democratic primaries were marked by a sharp contest between Obama and the initial front-runner, former first lady and Senator Hillary Clinton, as well as other challengers who dropped out before most of the primaries were held, including Senators John Edwards and Joe Biden.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton's victory in the New Hampshire primary made her the first woman to win a major party's presidential primary.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After a long primary season, Obama narrowly secured the Democratic nomination in June 2008 and selected Biden as his running mate.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush's popularity had significantly declined during his second term, which was attributed to the growing disdain for the Iraq War, his response to Hurricane Katrina, the Abu Ghraib torture controversy, and the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McCain opted to distance himself from Bush and did not campaign with him, nor did Bush appear in person at the 2008 Republican National Convention, although he did endorse McCain.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Obama strongly opposed the Iraq War, as well as a troop surge that had begun in 2007, while McCain supported the war.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Obama campaigned on the theme that "Washington must change", while McCain emphasized his experience.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McCain's decision to suspend his campaign during the height of the financial crisis backfired as voters viewed his response as erratic.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He also won every state in the Great Lakes region.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Article Two of the United States Constitution says that the president and vice president of the United States must be natural-born citizens of the United States, at least 35 years old, and residents of the United States for at least 14 years.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Candidates for president typically seek the nomination of a political party, in which case each party devises a method (such as a primary election) to choose a candidate for the position.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Traditionally, the primaries are indirect elections where voters cast ballots for a slate of party delegates pledged to a particular candidate.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The party's delegates then officially nominate a candidate to run on the party's behalf.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The general election in November is also an indirect election, where voters cast ballots for a slate of members of the Electoral College; these electors in turn directly elect the president and vice president.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush, a Republican and former governor of Texas, was ineligible to seek reelection to a third term due to the Twenty-second Amendment; in accordance with Section 1 of the Twentieth Amendment, his term expired at noon Eastern Standard Time on January 20, 2009.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Media speculation had begun almost immediately after the results of the 2004 presidential election were released.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the 2006 midterm elections, the Democrats regained majorities in both houses of the U.S.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Early polls taken before anyone had announced a candidacy had shown Senators Hillary Clinton and Barack Obama as the most popular potential Democratic candidates.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Edwards was one of the first to formally announce his candidacy for the presidency, on December 28, 2006.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This run would be his second attempt at the presidency.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton announced intentions to run in the Democratic primaries on January 20, 2007.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Obama announced his candidacy on February 10 in his home state of Illinois.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Early in the year, the support for Barack Obama started to increase in the polls and he passed Clinton for the top spot in Iowa; he ended up winning the caucus in that state, with Edwards coming in second and Clinton in third.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Obama's win was fueled mostly by first time caucus-goers and Independents and showed voters viewed him as the "candidate of change".
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Iowa has since been viewed as the state that jump-started Obama's campaign and set him on track to win both the nomination and the presidency.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After the Iowa caucus, Biden and Connecticut Senator Chris Dodd withdrew from the nomination contest.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Obama became the new front runner in New Hampshire, when his poll numbers skyrocketed after his Iowa victory.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Clinton campaign was struggling after a huge loss in Iowa and no strategy beyond the early primaries and caucuses.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] According to *The Vancouver Sun*, campaign strategists had "mapped a victory scenario that envisioned the former first lady wrapping up the Democratic presidential nomination by Super Tuesday on Feb.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] 5." In what is considered a turning point for her campaign, Clinton had a strong performance at the Saint Anselm College, ABC, and Facebook debates several days before the New Hampshire primary as well as an emotional interview in a public broadcast live on TV.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton won that primary by 2% of the vote, contrary to the predictions of pollsters who consistently had her trailing Obama for a few days up to the primary date.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton's win was the first time a woman had ever won a major American party's presidential primary for the purposes of delegate selection.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On January 30, 2008, after placing in third in the New Hampshire and South Carolina primaries, Edwards announced that he was suspending his campaign for the presidency, but he did not initially endorse any remaining candidates.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Super Tuesday was February 5, 2008, when the largest-ever number of simultaneous state primary elections was held.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Super Tuesday ended up leaving the Democrats in a virtual tie, with Obama amassing 847 delegates to Clinton's 834 from the 23 states that held Democratic primaries.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] California was one of the Super Tuesday states that could provide a large number of delegates to the candidates.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Obama trailed in the California polling by an average of 6.0% before the primary; he ended up losing that state by 8.3% of the vote.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Some analysts cited a large Latino turnout that voted for Clinton as the deciding factor.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Louisiana, Nebraska, Hawaii, Wisconsin, U.S.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Virgin Islands, the District of Columbia, Maryland, and Virginia primaries and the Washington and Maine caucuses all took place after Super Tuesday in February.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Obama won all of them, giving him 10 consecutive victories after Super Tuesday.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On March 4, Hillary Clinton carried Ohio and Rhode Island in the Democratic primaries; some considered these wins, especially Ohio, a "surprise upset" by 10%, although she did lead in the polling averages in both states.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] She also carried the primary in Texas, but Obama won the Texas caucuses held the same day and netted more delegates from the state than Clinton.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Although Obama made a strong effort to win Pennsylvania, Hillary Clinton won that primary by nearly 10%, with approximately 55% of the vote.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Obama had outspent Clinton three to one in Pennsylvania, but his comment at a San Francisco fundraiser that small-town Americans "cling" to guns and religion drew sharp criticism from the Clinton campaign and may have hurt his chances in the Keystone State.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In addition, Clinton had several advantages in Pennsylvania.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Throughout the primary process, she relied on the support of older, white, working class voters.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton, however, had received the endorsement of more superdelegates than Obama.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On May 6, North Carolina and Indiana held their Democratic presidential primaries.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton and Obama campaigned aggressively there before the voting took place.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Polling had shown Obama a few points ahead in North Carolina and Clinton similarly leading in Indiana.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the actual results, Obama outperformed the polls by several points in both states, winning by a significant margin in North Carolina and losing by only 1.1% in Indiana (50.56% to 49.44%).
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After these primaries, most pundits declared that it had become "increasingly improbable," if not impossible, for Clinton to win the nomination.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The small win in Indiana barely kept her campaign alive for the next month.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Although she did manage to win the majority of the remaining primaries and delegates, it was not enough to overcome Obama's substantial delegate lead.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] During late 2007, the two parties adopted rules against states' moving their primaries to an earlier date in the year.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] For the Republicans, the penalty for this violation was supposed to be the loss of half the state party's delegates to the convention.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Democratic penalty was the complete exclusion from the national convention of delegates from states that broke these rules.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Democratic Party allowed only four states to hold elections before February 5, 2008.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton won a majority of delegates and popular votes from both states (though 40% voted uncommitted in Michigan) and subsequently led a fight to seat all the Florida and Michigan delegates.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] There was some speculation that the fight over the delegates could last until the convention in August.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On May 31, 2008, the Rules and Bylaws Committee of the Democratic Party reached a compromise on the Florida and Michigan delegate situation.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The committee decided to seat delegates from Michigan and Florida at the convention in August, but to only award each a half-vote.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The major political party nomination process (technically) continues through June of an election year.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In previous cycles, the candidates were effectively chosen by the end of the primaries held in March, but, in this cycle, Barack Obama did not win enough delegates to secure the nomination until June 3, after a 17-month campaign against Hillary Clinton.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He had a wide lead in states won, while Clinton had won majorities in several of the larger states.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Now, because a form of proportional representation and popular vote decided Democratic state delegate contests, numbers were close between Clinton and Obama.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] By May, Clinton claimed to hold a lead in the popular vote, but the Associated Press found that her numbers were "accurate only" in one close scenario.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In June, after the last of the primaries had taken place, Obama secured the Democratic nomination for president, with the help of multiple super delegate endorsements (most of the super delegates had refused to declare their support for either candidate until the primaries were completed).
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He was the first African American to win the nomination of a major political party in the United States.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] For several days, Clinton refused to concede the race, although she signaled her presidential campaign was ending in a post-primary speech on June 3 in her home state of New York.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] She finally conceded the nomination to Obama on June 7.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] She pledged her full support to the presumptive nominee and vowed to do everything she could to help him get elected.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton became the Democratic presidential nominee 8 years later, but lost the general election to Donald Trump.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 2008 election was also the third presidential election since 1896 in which neither the incumbent president, the incumbent vice president, nor a current or former member of the incumbent president's Cabinet won the nomination of either major party the others being 1920 and 1952.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] With no members of the Bush administration emerging as major contenders for the Republican nomination, the Republican race was as open as the Democratic race.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Immediately after the 2006 midterm elections, media pundits began speculating, as they did about the Democrats, about potential Republican candidates for president in 2008.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In November 2006, former New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani led in the polls, followed closely by Arizona Senator John McCain.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The media speculated that Giuliani's pro-choice stance on abortion and McCain's age and support of the unpopular Iraq War would be detriments to their candidacies.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Giuliani remained the frontrunner in the polls throughout most of 2007, with McCain and former Tennessee Senator Fred Thompson fighting for second place.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Arkansas Governor Mike Huckabee, Giuliani, former Massachusetts governor Mitt Romney, and Texas Representative Ron Paul announced their candidacies on January 28, February 5, February 13, and March 12, respectively.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McCain officially announced his candidacy on March 1, 2007, after several informal announcements.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the third quarter of 2007, the top four GOP (Republican) fundraisers were Romney, Giuliani, Thompson, and Ron Paul.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] MSNBC's Chuck Todd christened Giuliani and John McCain the front runners after the second Republican presidential debate in early 2007.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Huckabee, winner of Iowa, had little to no money and hoped for at least a third-place finish in New Hampshire.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McCain eventually displaced Rudy Giuliani and Romney as the front runner in New Hampshire.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McCain staged a turnaround victory, having been written off by the pundits and polling in single digits less than a month before the race.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] With the Republicans stripping Michigan and Florida of half their delegates for moving their primaries into January 2008 against party rules, the race for the nomination was based there.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McCain meanwhile managed a small victory over Huckabee in South Carolina, setting him up for a larger and more important victory over Romney in Florida, which held a closed primary on January 29.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] By this time, after several scandals, no success in the early primaries, and a third-place finish in Florida, Giuliani conceded the nomination and endorsed John McCain the next day.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McCain was also endorsed in February by California Governor Arnold Schwarzenegger before the California primary took place on Super Tuesday.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This gave him a significant boost in the polls for the state's primary, which awarded the greatest number of delegates of all the states.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On Super Tuesday, McCain won his home state of Arizona, taking all 53 delegates.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He also won nearly all of California's 173 delegates, the largest of the Super Tuesday prizes.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McCain also scored wins in seven other states, picking up 574 delegates.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Huckabee was the "surprise performer", winning 5 states and 218 delegates.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Two days later, Romney suspended his presidential campaign, saying that if he stayed in the race, he would "forestall the launch of a national campaign and be making it easier for Senator Clinton or Obama to win".
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His departure left Huckabee and Paul as McCain's only major challengers in the remaining primaries and caucuses.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Louisiana, the District of Columbia, Kansas, Wisconsin, and Washington held primaries in February after Super Tuesday.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Despite McCain picking up big victories, Huckabee won Louisiana and Kansas.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McCain narrowly carried the Washington caucuses over Huckabee and Paul, who amassed a large showing.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Virgin Islands and Puerto Rico closed February for the Republicans.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After Super Tuesday, John McCain had become the clear front runner, but by the end of February, he still had not acquired enough delegates to secure the nomination.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In March, John McCain clinched the Republican nomination after sweeping all four primaries, Texas, Ohio, Vermont, and Rhode Island, putting him over the top of the 1,191 delegates required to win the GOP nomination.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Mike Huckabee then conceded the race to McCain, leaving Ron Paul, who had just 16 delegates, as his only remaining opponent.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Romney would eventually become the Republican presidential nominee 4 years later, which he then lost to Barack Obama.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Along with the Democratic and Republican parties, three other parties nominated candidates with ballot access in enough states to win the minimum 270 electoral votes needed to win the election.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] These were the Constitution Party, the Green Party, and the Libertarian Party.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In addition, independent candidate Ralph Nader ran his own campaign.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Constitution Party nominated writer, pastor, and conservative talk show host Chuck Baldwin for president, and attorney Darrell Castle from Tennessee for vice president.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] While campaigning, Baldwin voiced his opposition to the Iraq War, the Sixteenth Amendment, *Roe v.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Wade*, the IRS, and the Federal Reserve.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Green Party nominated former Democratic representative Cynthia McKinney from Georgia for president, and political activist Rosa Clemente from New York for vice president.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McKinney campaigned on a platform that supported single-payer universal health care, the withdrawal of American troops from Iraq and Afghanistan, reparations for African Americans, and the creation of a Department of Peace.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Libertarian Party nominated former Republican representative Bob Barr from Georgia for president, and his former rival for the Libertarian nomination Wayne Allyn Root from Nevada, for vice president.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] During the 2008 presidential campaign, Barr advocated a reworking or abolition of the income tax and opposed the war in Iraq and the Patriot Act.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Until the onset of the 2008 financial crisis, the unpopular Iraq War was a key issue during the campaign.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] John McCain supported the war while Barack Obama opposed it (Obama's early and strong opposition to the war helped him stand out against the other Democratic candidates during the primaries, as well as stand out to a war-weary electorate during the general campaign).
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Though McCain meant it as a peacetime presence like the United States maintained in Germany and Japan after World War II, his statement that the United States could be in Iraq for as much as the next 50 to 100 years would prove costly.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Obama used it against him as part of his strategy to tie him to the unpopular President Bush.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] John McCain's support for the troop 'surge' employed by General David Petraeus, which was one of several factors credited with improving the security situation in Iraq, may have boosted McCain's stance on the issue in voters' minds.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McCain (who supported the invasion) argued that his support for the successful surge showed his superior judgment.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, Obama was quick to remind voters that there would have been no need for a "surge" had there been no war at all, thus questioning McCain's judgment.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush had become increasingly unpopular among Americans by late 2005 due in part by the growing unpopularity of the Iraq War domestically and internationally, as well as Bush's handling of the 2008 financial crisis and Hurricane Katrina in 2005.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] By the time Obama was elected as President of the United States on November 4, 2008, Bush's approval rating was in the low to mid 20s and his disapproval grew increasingly significant, being in the high 60s, and even low 70s in some polls.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Polls consistently showed that his approval ratings among American voters had averaged around 30 percent.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In March 2008, Bush endorsed McCain at the White House, but did not make a single appearance for McCain during the campaign.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush appeared at the 2008 GOP convention only through a live video broadcast.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He chose not to appear in person due to disaster events in the Gulf of Mexico in the aftermath of Hurricane Gustav.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Although he supported the war in Iraq, McCain made an effort to show that he had disagreed with Bush on many other key issues such as climate change.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] During the entire general election campaign, Obama countered by pointing out in ads and at numerous campaign rallies that McCain had claimed in an interview that he voted with Bush 90% of the time, and congressional voting records supported this for the years Bush was in office.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In addition, McCain suffered from the ill effects of his captivity in North Vietnam and reportedly had difficulty lifting his arms above his head.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His age in particular was considered a liability against the youthful Senator Obama, who was nearly twenty-five years his junior.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McCain, by comparison, was born before World War II and belonged to the Silent Generation.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Much like Bob Dole, McCain attempted to counter these charges by releasing all of his medical records, something Obama did not do.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McCain's wife Cindy dismissed concerns about his health by arguing that "We went hiking the Grand Canyon last summer and [John] did great and had no trouble keeping up with us." McCain also appeared at several campaign stops with his still-active 95-year-old mother.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In a speech on the House floor, Pennsylvania Congressman John Murtha criticized McCain's age by saying "Seven presidents have come and gone since I've been in Congress, and I saw the toll the job took on each one of them." If elected, McCain would have been the first president born in the 1930s.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McCain ultimately died in 2018, just one year after the completion of Obama's second term.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Like the Clinton campaign in 1996, Obama avoided discussing McCain's age directly, instead preferring to simply call his ideas and message "old" and "old hat".
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He also made a strong appeal to youth voters and back during his primary contest with Hillary Clinton, had stated "When I watched the feud between the Clintons and [Newt Gingrich] unfold during the 1990s, I was reminded of old quarrels started on college campuses long ago.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It's time for a new generation to take over." Obama's active use of a Blackberry and other modern technology also stood in contrast to the Arizona Senator's admission that he was an infrequent user of email and the internet.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McCain's service in Vietnam, while marketable to baby boomers, was referred to as "unimportant" to younger voters.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Obama promised "universal health care, full employment, a green America, and an America respected instead of feared by its enemies".
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Polls regularly found the general electorate as a whole divided more evenly between 'change' and 'experience' as candidate qualities than the Democratic primary electorate, which split in favor of 'change' by a nearly 2–1 margin.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Advantages for McCain and Obama on experience and the ability to bring change, respectively, remained steady through the November 4 election.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, final pre-election polling found that voters considered Obama's inexperience less of an impediment than McCain's association with sitting president George W.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush, an association which was rhetorically framed by the Obama campaign throughout the election season as "more of the same".
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] McCain appeared to undercut his line of attack by picking first-term Alaska governor Sarah Palin to be his running mate.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Palin had been governor only since 2006, and before that had been a council member and mayor of Wasilla.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Palin also came off as more down-to-earth and relatable to average Americans than McCain, widely criticized as a "Beltway insider".
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, media interviews suggested that Palin lacked knowledge on certain key issues, and they cast doubt among many voters about her qualifications to be vice president or president.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In this regard, her inexperience was also a liability when McCain's age and health were factored in—there was a higher-than-normal probability of Palin succeeding to the presidency.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] "One 72-year-old heartbeat away from the presidency" became a popular anti-GOP slogan.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] She also came under attack on everything from her 17-year-old daughter giving birth to a child out of wedlock to actively participating in hunting moose and other animals.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Because of Palin's conservative views, there was also concern that she would alienate independents and moderates, two groups that pundits observed McCain would need to win the election.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Polls taken in the last few months of the presidential campaign and exit polls conducted on Election Day showed the economy as the top concern for voters.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the fall of 2008, many news sources were reporting that the economy was suffering its most serious downturn since the Great Depression.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] During this period, John McCain's election prospects fell with several politically costly comments about the economy.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On August 20, John McCain said in an interview with *Politico* that he was uncertain how many houses he and his wife, Cindy, owned; "I think—I'll have my staff get to you," he told the media outlet.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Both on the stump and in Obama's political ad, "Seven", the gaffe was used to portray McCain as somebody unable to relate to the concerns of ordinary Americans.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Despite this decision, McCain was portrayed as somebody not playing a significant role in the negotiations for the first version of the bill, which fell short of passage in the House.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He eventually decided to attend the first presidential debate on September 26, despite Congress' lack of immediate action on the bill.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His ineffectiveness in the negotiations and his reversal in decision to attend the debates were seized upon to portray McCain as erratic in his response to the economy.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Days later, a second version of the original bailout bill was passed by both the House and Senate, with Obama, his vice presidential running mate Joe Biden, and McCain all voting for the measure (Hillary Clinton would as well).
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] All the aforementioned remarks and campaign issues hurt McCain's standing with voters.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] All these also occurred after the onset of the 2008 financial crisis and after McCain's poll numbers had started to fall.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Although sound bites of all of these "missteps" were played repeatedly on national television, many pundits and analysts say that the actual financial crisis and economic conditions caused McCain's large drop in support in mid-September and severely damaged his campaign.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] John McCain's proposals focused on open-market competition rather than government funding or control.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] At the heart of his plan were tax credits – $2,500 for individuals and $5,000 for families who do not subscribe to or do not have access to health care through their employer.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] To help people who are denied coverage by insurance companies due to pre-existing conditions, McCain proposed working with states to create what he calls a "Guaranteed Access Plan".
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Barack Obama called for universal health care.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His health care plan proposed creating a National Health Insurance Exchange that would include both private insurance plans and a Medicare-like government run option.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Coverage would be guaranteed regardless of health status, and premiums would not vary based on health status either.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It would have required parents to cover their children, but did not require adults to buy insurance.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Critics of McCain's plan argued that it would not significantly reduce the number of uninsured Americans, would increase costs, reduce consumer protections and lead to less generous benefit packages.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Critics of Obama's plan argued that it would increase federal regulation of private health insurance without addressing the underlying incentives behind rising health care spending.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Mark Pauly suggested that a combination of the two approaches would work better than either one alone.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A poll released in early November 2008 found that voters supporting Obama listed health care as their second priority; voters supporting McCain listed it as fourth, tied with the war in Iraq.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Affordability was the primary health care priority among both sets of voters.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Obama voters were more likely than McCain voters to believe government can do much about health care costs.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The United States presidential election of 2008 was sponsored by the Commission on Presidential Debates (CPD), a bipartisan organization that sponsored four debates that occurred at various locations around the United States (U.S.) in September and October 2008.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Three of the debates involved the presidential nominees, and one involved the vice-presidential nominees.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Another debate was sponsored by the Columbia University political union and took place there on October 19.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] All candidates who could theoretically win the 270 electoral votes needed to win the election were invited, and Ralph Nader, Cynthia McKinney, and Chuck Baldwin agreed to attend.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Amy Goodman, principal host of *Democracy Now!*, moderated.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It was broadcast on cable by C-SPAN and on the Internet by Break-the-Matrix.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The reported cost of campaigning for president has increased significantly in recent years.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In January 2007, Federal Election Commission Chairman Michael E.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Toner estimated that the 2008 race would be a $1 billion election, and that to be taken seriously, a candidate would have needed to raise at least $100 million by the end of 2007.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] According to required campaign filings as reported by the Federal Election Commission (FEC), 148 candidates for all parties collectively raised $1,644,712,232 and spent $1,601,104,696 for the primary and general campaigns combined through November 24, 2008.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Elections analysts and political pundits issue probabilistic forecasts of the composition of the Electoral College.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] These forecasts use a variety of factors to estimate the likelihood of each candidate winning the Electoral College electors for that state.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Below is a list of states considered competitive by at least one of *The Cook Political Report*, *RealClearPolitics*, and *FiveThirtyEight*; states that are deemed to be "safe" or "solid" by all three forecasters are excluded.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Howard Dean collected large contributions through the Internet in his 2004 primary run.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In 2008, candidates went even further to reach out to Internet users through their own sites and such sites as YouTube, MySpace, and Facebook.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On December 16, 2007, Ron Paul collected $6 million, more money on a single day through Internet donations than any presidential candidate in US history.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 2008 election was the first time that a majority of the voting-age population preferred to get their news from the Internet.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Not only did the Internet allow candidates to raise money, but also it gave them a tool to appeal to newer and younger demographics.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Political pundits were now evaluating candidates based on their social media following.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Senator Barack Obama's victory is credited to his competitive edge in social media and Internet following.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Obama had over 2 million American supporters on Facebook and 100,000 followers on Twitter, while McCain attracted only 600,000 Facebook supporters (likes) and 4,600 followers on Twitter.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Obama's YouTube channel held 115,000 subscribers and more than 97 million video views.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Obama had maintained a similar advantage over Senator Hillary Clinton in the Democratic primary.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Obama's edge in social media was crucial to the election outcome.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] According to a study by the Pew Internet and American Life project, 35 percent of Americans relied on online video for election news.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Ten percent of Americans used social networking sites to learn about the election.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 2008 election showed huge increases in Internet use.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Another study done after the election gave a lot of insight on young voters.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Thirty-seven percent of Americans ages 18–24 got election news from social networking sites.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Almost a quarter of Americans saw something about the election in an online video.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] YouTube and other online video outlets allowed candidates to advertise in ways like never before.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Republican Party in particular was criticized for not adequately using social media and other means to reach young voters.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Anonymous and semi-anonymous smear campaigns, traditionally done with fliers and push calling, also spread to the Internet.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Organizations specializing in the production and distribution of viral material, such as Brave New Films, emerged; such organizations have been said to be having a growing influence on American politics.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Allegations of voter list purges using unlawful criteria caused controversy in at least six swing states: Colorado, Indiana, Ohio, Michigan, Nevada and North Carolina.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Governor of Montana, John Bohlinger, accused the Montana Republican Party of vote caging to purge 6,000 voters from three counties which trend Democratic.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Allegations arose in Michigan that the Republican Party planned to challenge the eligibility of voters based on lists of foreclosed homes.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The campaign of Democratic presidential nominee Barack Obama filed a lawsuit challenging this.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The House Judiciary Committee wrote to the Department of Justice requesting an investigation.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Libertarian candidate Bob Barr filed a lawsuit in Texas to have Obama and McCain removed from the ballot in that state.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] His campaign alleged that both of the candidates had missed the August 26 deadline to file and had been included on the ballot in violation of Texas election law.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Neither Obama nor McCain had been confirmed as the candidate of their respective parties at the time of the deadline.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Texas Supreme Court dismissed the lawsuit without explanation.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In Ohio, identified by both parties as a key state, allegations surfaced from both Republicans and Democrats that individuals from out of state were moving to the state temporarily and attempting to vote despite not meeting the state's requirement of permanent residency for more than 29 days.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Franklin County Board of Elections referred 55 cases of possible voting irregularities to the local prosecutor.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Three groups attracted particular notice: 'Vote from Home,' 'Vote Today Ohio,' and 'Drop Everything and Come to Ohio.' Vote from Home attracted the most attention when thirteen of the group's members moved to the same location in eastern Columbus.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Members of the group organized by Marc Gustafson, including several Marshall and Rhodes scholars studying at Oxford University, settled with Franklin County Prosecutor Ron O'Brien to have their challenged ballots withdrawn.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Obama campaign and others alleged that members of the McCain campaign had also voted without properly establishing residency.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Since 1953, only six people in Ohio have gone to prison for illegal voting.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Republicans and independents leveled significant criticism at media outlets' coverage of the presidential election season.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] An October 22, 2008 Pew Research Center poll estimated 70% of registered voters believed journalists wanted Barack Obama to win the election, as opposed to 9% for John McCain.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Another Pew survey, conducted after the election, found that 67% of voters thought that the press fairly covered Obama, versus 30% who viewed the coverage as unfair.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Regarding McCain, 53% of voters viewed his press coverage as fair versus 44% who characterized it as unfair.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Among affiliated Democrats, 83% believed the press fairly covered Obama; just 22% of Republicans thought the press was fair to McCain.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] At the February debate, Tim Russert of NBC News was criticized for what some perceived as disproportionately tough questioning of Democratic presidential contender Hillary Clinton.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Among the questions, Russert had asked Clinton, but not Obama, to provide the name of the new Russian President (Dmitry Medvedev).
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This was later parodied on *Saturday Night Live*.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In October 2007, liberal commentators accused Russert of harassing Clinton over the issue of supporting drivers' licenses for illegal immigrants.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] On April 16, ABC News hosted a debate in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Moderators Charles Gibson and George Stephanopoulos were criticized by viewers, bloggers and media critics for the poor quality of their questions.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Many viewers said they considered some of the questions irrelevant when measured against the importance of the faltering economy or the Iraq War.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Included in that category were continued questions about Obama's former pastor, Senator Hillary Clinton's assertion that she had to duck sniper fire in Bosnia more than a decade prior, and Senator Obama's not wearing an American flag pin.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The moderators focused on campaign gaffes and some believed they focused too much on Obama.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] *Time* magazine columnist Mark Halperin stated that the media during the 2008 election had a "blind, almost slavish" worship of Obama.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Project for Excellence in Journalism and Harvard University's Joan Shorenstein Center on the Press, Politics and Public Policy conducted a study of 5,374 media narratives and assertions about the presidential candidates from January 1 through March 9, 2008.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The study found that Obama received 69% favorable coverage and Clinton received 67%, compared to only 43% favorable media coverage of McCain.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Another study by the Center for Media and Public Affairs at George Mason University found the media coverage of Obama to be 72% negative from June 8 to July 21 compared to 57% negative for McCain.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] An October 29 study found 29% of stories about Obama to be negative, compared to 57% of stories about McCain being negative.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The majority of states allowed early voting, with all states allowing some form of absentee voting.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Voters cast votes for listed presidential candidates but were actually selecting representatives for their state's Electoral College slate.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] A McCain victory quickly became improbable as Obama amassed early wins in his home state of Illinois, the Northeast, and the critical battleground states of Ohio and Pennsylvania by 9:30 pm Eastern Standard Time.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Obama won the entire Northeast by comfortable margins and the Great Lakes states of Michigan, Wisconsin, and Minnesota by double digits.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] McCain held on to traditionally Republican states like North Dakota, South Dakota, Nebraska (though notably, Obama did win an electoral vote from Nebraska's 2nd congressional district), Kansas, Oklahoma, Montana, Utah, Idaho, Wyoming, and his home state of Arizona.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Out of the southern states, Obama won Florida, North Carolina, Delaware, Maryland, and Virginia.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Obama also won the hotly contested states of Iowa and New Mexico, which Al Gore had won in 2000 and George W.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Also, for only the second time since 1936 (1964 being the other), Indiana went Democratic, giving Obama all eight Great Lakes states, the first time a presidential candidate had won all of them since Richard Nixon in 1972.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] CNN and Fox News called Virginia for Obama shortly before 11:00 pm, leaving him only 50 electoral votes shy of victory with only six West Coast states (California, Oregon, Washington, Idaho, Alaska, and Hawaii) still voting.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] All American networks called the election in favor of Obama at 11:00 pm as the polls closed on the West Coast.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Obama was immediately declared the winner in California, Oregon, Washington, and Hawaii, McCain won Idaho, and the Electoral College totals were updated to 297 for Obama and 146 for McCain (270 are needed to win).
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] McCain gave a concession speech half an hour later in his hometown of Phoenix, Arizona.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Obama appeared just before midnight Eastern Time in Grant Park, Chicago, in front of a crowd of 250,000 people to deliver his victory speech.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Later on election night, after Obama was named the winner, he picked up several more wins in swing states in which the polls had shown a close race.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] These included Florida, Indiana, Virginia, and the western states of Colorado and Nevada.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] All of these states had been carried by Bush in 2004.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] North Carolina and the bellwether state of Missouri remained undecided for several days.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Eventually Obama was declared the winner in North Carolina and McCain in Missouri, with Obama pulling out a rare win in Nebraska's 2nd congressional district.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This put the projected electoral vote count at 365 for Obama and 173 for McCain.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Obama's victories in the populous swing states of Florida, Ohio, Pennsylvania, North Carolina, and Virginia contributed to his decisive win.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The presidential electors cast their ballots for president and vice president, and Congress tallied these votes on January 8, 2009.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The voter turnout for this election was broadly predicted to be high by American standards, and a record number of votes were cast.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The final tally of total votes counted was 131.3 million, compared to 122.3 million in 2004 (which also boasted the highest record since 1968, the last presidential election before the voting age was lowered to 18).
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Expressed as a percentage of eligible voters, 131.2 million votes could reflect a turnout as high as 63.0% of eligible voters, which would be the highest since 1960.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This 63.0% turnout rate is based on an estimated eligible voter population of 208,323,000.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Another estimate puts the eligible voter population at 213,313,508, resulting in a turnout rate of 61.6%, which would be the highest turnout rate since 1968.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Broken down by age group, voters under 35 voted for Obama by a large majority with McCain most popular among voters over 60.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Voters between 35 and 59 were nearly split 50/50 between the two candidates.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] American University's Center for the Study of the American Electorate released a report on November 6, 2008, two days after the election, which concluded that the anticipated increase in turnout had failed to materialize.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] That report was the basis for some news articles that indicated voter turnout failed to meet expectations.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] When the remaining votes were counted after the release of the report, the total number of votes cast in the presidential election was raised to 131.2 million, which surpassed the American University report's preliminary estimate of 126.5 to 128.5 million voters by a factor of between 2% and 4%.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The election saw increased participation from African Americans, who made up 13.0% of the electorate, versus 11.1% in 2004.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] According to exit polls, over 95% of African Americans voted for Obama.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This played a critical role in Southern states such as North Carolina.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] 74% of North Carolina's registered African American voters turned out, as opposed to 69% of North Carolinians in general, with Obama carrying 100% (with rounding) of African-American females and African Americans age 18 to 29, according to exit polling.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This was also the case in Virginia, where much higher turnout among African Americans propelled Obama to victory in the former Republican stronghold.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Even in southern states in which Obama was unsuccessful, such as Georgia and Mississippi, due to large African American turnout he was much more competitive than John Kerry in 2004.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] No other candidate had ballot access in enough states to win 270 electoral votes.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] All six candidates appeared on the ballot for a majority of the voters, while the 17 other listed candidates were available to no more than 30% of the voters.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In Nevada, 6,267 votes were cast for "None of These Candidates".
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In the three states that officially keep track of "blank" votes for president, 103,193 votes were recorded as "blank".
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] More than 100,000 write-in votes were cast and recorded for a scattering of other candidates, including 62 votes for "Santa Claus" (in ten states) and 11 votes for "Mickey Mouse" (in five states).
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] According to the Federal Election Commission, an unusually high number of "miscellaneous" write-ins were cast for president in 2008, including 112,597 tallied in the 17 states that record votes for non-listed candidates.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] There were more presidential candidates on the ballot than at any other time in U.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] S. history, except for the 1992 election, which also had 23 candidates listed in at least one state.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Of the 3,154 counties/districts/independent cities making returns, McCain won the most popular votes in 2,270 (71.97%) while Obama carried 884 (28.03%).
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Popular vote totals are from the official Federal Election Commission report.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The results of the electoral vote were certified by Congress on January 8, 2009.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The following table records the official vote tallies for each state for those presidential candidates who were listed on ballots in enough states to have a theoretical chance for a majority in the Electoral College.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] State popular vote results are from the official Federal Election Commission report.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The column labeled "Margin" shows Obama's margin of victory over McCain (the margin is negative for states and districts won by McCain).
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Note: Maine and Nebraska each allow for their electoral votes to be split between candidates.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In both states, two electoral votes are awarded to the winner of the statewide race and one electoral vote is awarded to the winner of each congressional district.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Obama, having a white mother and Kenyan father of the Luo ethnic group, became the first African American as well as the first biracial president.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Several black people had previously run for president, including Shirley Chisholm, Jesse Jackson, Lenora Fulani, Carol Moseley Braun, Alan Keyes, and Al Sharpton, though Obama was the first one ever to win the nomination of a major party, let alone the general election.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The Obama-Biden ticket was the first winning ticket consisting of two sitting senators since 1960 (John F.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Johnson), and Obama became the first Northern Democratic president since Kennedy.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Also, Obama became the first Democratic candidate to win a majority of the popular vote since Jimmy Carter in 1976, the first to win a majority of both votes and states since Lyndon B.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Johnson in 1964, and the first Northern Democrat to win a majority of both votes and states since Franklin D.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Additionally, Obama became the first Northern Democrat to win any state in the former Confederacy since Hubert Humphrey won Texas in 1968.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Furthermore, his margin of victory, 7.27%, was the largest for any victor since Bill Clinton in 1996 and for any first-term president since George H.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This was the first presidential election since 1952 in which neither of the major-party nominees was the incumbent president or vice-president.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This is the only election where both major party nominees were Senators.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Prior to the election, commentators discussed whether Obama would be able to redraw the electoral map by winning states that had been voting for Republican candidates in recent decades.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] He won every region of the country by double digits except the South, which John McCain won by nine percent, although Obama nonetheless carried Delaware, the District of Columbia, Maryland, North Carolina, Florida, and Virginia (the South as defined by the U.S.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] McCain won every state in the Deep South, where white voters had generally supported Republican candidates by increasingly large margins in the previous few decades.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Obama won all of the 2004 swing states (states that either Kerry or Bush won by less than 5%) by a margin of 8.5 percent or more except for Ohio, which he carried by 4.5 percent.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Obama also defied political bellwethers, becoming the first person to win the presidency while losing Missouri since 1956 and while losing Kentucky and Tennessee since 1960.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Indiana and Virginia voted for the Democratic nominee for the first time since 1964, as did a solitary electoral vote from Nebraska's 2nd congressional district.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Indiana would return to being a reliably red state in subsequent elections; Virginia, however, has been won by Democrats in every presidential election since and would grow increasingly Democratic at the state level.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] North Carolina, which Obama was the first Democrat to carry since 1976, would return to the Republican column in the following elections, though only by narrow margins each time.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Obama was also relatively competitive in some traditionally Republican states he lost, notably Montana, which he lost by under 3%, and Georgia, which he lost by just 5%.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] He is also the only 21st-century Democrat to lose North Dakota and South Dakota by just single digits.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] McCain remains the last presidential candidate to receive fewer than 200 electoral votes.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This was the first presidential election in which Nebraska split its electoral votes between two candidates.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Obama won the electoral vote from Nebraska's 2nd congressional district, largely comprising the city of Omaha.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Nebraska's other four electoral votes went to John McCain.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] As of 2024, this election is the last time that Indiana or North Carolina voted Democratic, and is also the most recent election where one of the nominees has since died.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Until 2024 this was also the most recent election in which any of the major presidential nominees had any military experience.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This election exhibited the continuation of some of the polarization trends evident in the 2000 and 2004 elections.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] McCain won whites 55–43 percent, while Obama won blacks 95–4 percent, Hispanics 67–31 percent, and Asians 62–35 percent.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Voters aged 18–29 voted for Obama by 66–32 percent while elderly voters backed McCain 53–45 percent.
[src:african-americans/2008-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The 25-year age gap between McCain and Obama was the widest in U.S. presidential election history among the top two candidates.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] The **2010 United States census** was the 23rd United States census.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] National Census Day, the reference day used for the census, was April 1, 2010.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] The census was taken via mail-in citizen self-reporting, with enumerators serving to spot-check randomly selected neighborhoods and communities.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] As part of a drive to increase the count's accuracy, 635,000 temporary enumerators were hired.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] The population of the United States was counted as 308,745,538, a 9.7% increase from the 2000 United States census.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] This was the first census in which all states recorded a population of over 500,000 people as well as the first in which all 100 largest cities recorded populations of over 200,000.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] It was the first census since 1930 that California did not record the largest population growth in absolute number.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Texas surpassed California's growth by 4.3 million to 3.4 million.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] As required by the United States Constitution, the U.S.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Census has been conducted every 10 years since 1790.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] The 2000 U.S. census was the previous census completed.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Census is required by law of people living in the United States in Title 13 of the United States Code.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] On January 25, 2010, Census Bureau Director Robert Groves personally inaugurated the 2010 census enumeration by counting World War II veteran Clifton Jackson, a resident of Noorvik, Alaska.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] More than 120 million census forms were delivered by the U.S.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] The number of forms mailed out or hand-delivered by the Census Bureau was approximately 134 million on April 1, 2010.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] The 2010 census national mail participation rate was 74%.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] From April through July 2010, census takers visited households that did not return a form, an operation called "non-response follow-up" (NRFU).
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Census Bureau delivered population information to the U.S. president for apportionment, and later in March 2011, complete redistricting data was delivered to states.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Personally identifiable information will be available in 2082.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] The Census Bureau did not use a long form for the 2010 census.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] In several previous censuses, one in six households received this long form, which asked for detailed social and economic information.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Were there any additional people staying here on April 1, 2010, that you did not include in Question 1?
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] What is Person 1's age and Person 1's date of birth?
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Is Person 1 of Hispanic, Latino, or Spanish origin?
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Does Person 1 sometimes live or stay somewhere else?
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] The form included space to repeat some or all of these questions for up to twelve residents total.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] In contrast to the 2000 census, an Internet response option was not offered, nor was the form available for download.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Detailed socioeconomic information collected during past censuses will continue to be collected through the American Community Survey.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] The survey provides data about communities in the United States on a 1-year or 3-year cycle, depending on the size of the community, rather than once every 10 years.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] A small percentage of the population on a rotating basis will receive the survey each year, and no household will receive it more than once every five years.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Census Bureau announced that it would count same-sex married couples.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] However, the final form did not contain a separate "same-sex married couple" option.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] When noting the relationship between household members, same-sex couples who are married could mark their spouses as being "Husband or wife", the same response given by opposite-sex married couples.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] An "unmarried partner" option was available for couples (whether same-sex or opposite-sex) who were not married.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] The Census 2010 Language Program was significantly expanded.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Language assistance in 49 languages in the 2000 Census was increased to 59 languages in Census 2000.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] In addition to English, Census questionnaire was available in five non-English languages: Spanish, Chinese (simplified), Korean, Vietnamese, and Russian.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] The 2010 census cost $13 billion, approximately $42 per capita; by comparison, the 2010 census per-capita cost for China was about US$1 and for India was US$0.40.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Operational costs were $5.4 billion, significantly under the $7 billion budget.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] In December 2010 the Government Accountability Office (GAO) noted that the cost of conducting the census has approximately doubled each decade since 1970.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] In a detailed 2004 report to Congress, the GAO called on the Census Bureau to address cost and design issues, and at that time, had estimated the 2010 census cost to be $11 billion.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Locke credited the management practices of Census Bureau director Robert Groves, citing in particular the decision to buy additional advertising in locations where responses lagged, which improved the overall response rate.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] The agency also has begun to rely more on questioning neighbors or other reliable third parties when a person could not be immediately reached at home, which reduced the cost of follow-up visits.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Census data for about 22% of U.S. households that did not reply by mail were based on such outside interviews, Groves said.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] In 2005, Lockheed Martin won a six-year, $500 million contract to capture and standardize data for the census.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] The contract included systems, facilities, and staffing.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] The final value of that contract was in excess of one billion dollars.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Information technology was about a quarter of the projected $11.3 billion cost of the decennial census.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] The use of high-speed document scanning technology, such as ImageTrac scanners developed by IBML, helped Lockheed Martin complete the project on schedule and under budget.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Due to the rise in social media and cell-phone usage in the U.S., the Census Bureau used research gathered through a cell-phone study in order to target media and ads to populations that were nonrespondents and promote census participation.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] This study also helped gauge the mindset of those who fail to respond, trying to figure out why.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] This was the first census to use hand-held computing devices with GPS capability, although they were only used for the address canvassing operation.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Enumerators (information gatherers) that had operational problems with the device understandably made negative reports.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] During the 2009 Senate confirmation hearings for Robert Groves, President Obama's Census Director appointee, there was much mention of contracting problems but very little criticism of the units themselves.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] The Census Bureau chose to conduct the primary operation, Non-Response Follow Up (NRFU), without using the handheld computing devices.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] There was a penalty of $100 for not completing some or all of the 2010 U.S.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Census Bureau director Robert Grove, however, wrote "the Census Bureau has rarely prosecuted failure to respond.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] While the rationale for the mandatory nature of the census still applies today, our message for the 2010 Census is about the common good benefits of participation".
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] The fine for non-participation is much lower than that for reporting false information.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] The Association of Community Organizations for Reform Now (ACORN) was given a contract to help publicize the importance of the census count and to encourage individuals to fill out their forms.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] In September 2009, after controversial undercover videos showing four ACORN staffers giving tax advice to a man and a woman posing as a prostitute, the bureau canceled ACORN's contract.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Various American celebrities, including Demi Lovato and Eva Longoria, were used in public service announcements targeting younger people to fill out census forms.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Wilmer Valderrama and Rosario Dawson have helped spread census awareness among young Hispanics, a historically low participating ethnicity in the U.S. census.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Rapper Ludacris also participated in efforts to spread awareness of the 2010 census.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] The Census Bureau hired about 635,000 people to find those U.S. residents who had not returned their forms by mail; as of May 28, 2010, 113 census workers had been victims of crime while conducting the census.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Some political conservatives and libertarians questioned the validity of the questions and even encouraged people to refuse to answer questions for privacy and constitutional reasons.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] As a result, the Census Bureau undertook an unprecedented advertising campaign targeted at encouraging white political conservatives to fill out their forms, in the hope of avoiding an undercount of this group.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] The 2010 U.S. census was the primary sponsor at NASCAR races in Atlanta, Bristol, and Martinsville, and sponsored the No.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] 16 Ford Fusion driven by Greg Biffle for part of the season, because of a marketing survey that indicated most NASCAR fans lean politically conservative.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] It also ran an advertisement during the 2010 Super Bowl, and hired singer Marie Osmond, who is thought to have many conservative fans, to publicize the census.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] The results of the 2010 census determined the number of seats that each state received in the United States House of Representatives starting with the 2012 elections.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Consequently, this affected the number of votes each state had in the Electoral College for the 2012 presidential election.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Because of population changes, eighteen states had changes in their number of seats.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Eight states gained at least one seat, and ten states lost at least one seat.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] The final result involved 12 seats being switched.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Some objected to the counting of persons who are in the United States illegally.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Senators David Vitter (R-LA) and Bob Bennett (R-UT) tried unsuccessfully to add questions on immigration status to the census form.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Organizations such as the Prison Policy Initiative argued that the census counts of incarcerated men and women as residents of prisons, rather than of their pre-incarceration addresses, skewed political clout and resulted in misleading demographic and population data.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Many residents of prisons counted on the 2010 census were those who identify as Black and Hispanic.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] This could lead to the loss of resources for underserved minority communities.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] The term "Negro" was used in the questionnaire as one of the options for African Americans (Question 9.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Black, African Am., or Negro) as a choice to describe one's race.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Census Bureau spokesman Jack Martin explained that "many older African-Americans identified themselves that way, and many still do.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Those who identify themselves as Negroes need to be included." The word was also used in the 2000 census, with over 56,000 people identifying themselves as "Negro".
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] In response to complaints over the word's inclusion on the 2010 census, the Census Bureau announced in 2013 that it would stop using "Negro" going forward, with the 2014 American Community Survey census form being the first without the word.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] The 2010 census contained ten questions about age, gender, ethnicity, home ownership, and household relationships.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Six of the ten questions were to be answered for each individual in the household.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Federal law has provisions for fining those who refuse to complete the census form.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Detroit Mayor Dave Bing held a press conference on March 22, 2011, to announce that the city would challenge its census results.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] The challenge, being led by the city's planning department, cited an inconsistency as an example showing a downtown census tract which lost only 60 housing units, but 1,400 people, implying that a downtown jail or dormitory was missed in canvassing.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] NYC Mayor Michael Bloomberg held a conference on March 27, 2011, to announce that the city would also challenge his city's census results, specifically the apparent undercounting in the boroughs of Queens and Brooklyn.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Bloomberg said that the numbers for Queens and Brooklyn, the two most populous boroughs, are implausible.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] According to the census, they grew by only 0.1% and 1.6%, respectively, while the other boroughs grew by between 3% and 5%.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] He also stated that the census showed improbably high numbers of vacant housing in vital neighborhoods such as Jackson Heights, Queens.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] The District of Columbia announced in August 2011 that it would also challenge its census results.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] The Mayor's Office claimed that the detailed information provided for 549 census blocks is "nonsensical", listing examples of census data that show housing units located in the middle of a street that does not actually exist.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] However, officials do not believe the city's total population will drastically change as a result of the challenge.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] The state with the highest percentage rate of growth was Nevada, while the state with the largest population increase was Texas.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] Michigan, the 8th largest by population, was the only state to lose population (although Puerto Rico, a U.S. territory, lost population as well), and the District of Columbia saw its first gain since the 1950s.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] The resident populations listed below do not include people living overseas.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] For Congressional apportionment, the sum of a state's resident population and its population of military personnel and federal contractors living overseas (but not other citizens overseas, such as missionaries or expatriate workers) is used.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] These are core metropolitan rankings versus combined statistical areas.
[src:african-americans/2010-united-states-census] For full list with current data, go to metropolitan statistics.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 6, 2012.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Incumbent Democratic president Barack Obama and his running mate, incumbent vice president Joe Biden, were elected to a second term.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] They defeated the Republican ticket of former Massachusetts governor Mitt Romney and Wisconsin congressman Paul Ryan.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Obama and Biden were re-nominated by their party without strong opposition in the way.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Meanwhile, the Republican Party experienced a competitive primary, with Romney consistently competitive in the polls and winning the support of many party leaders, but facing challenges from a number of more conservative contenders.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Romney secured his party's nomination in May, defeating former senator Rick Santorum, former speaker of the House and Georgia congressman Newt Gingrich, and Texas congressman Ron Paul, among other candidates.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The campaigns focused heavily on domestic issues, and debate centered largely around sound responses to the Great Recession along with long-term federal budget issues, the future of social insurance programs, and the Affordable Care Act.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Foreign policy was also discussed, including the end of the Iraq War in 2011, military spending, the Iranian nuclear program, and appropriate counteractions to terrorism.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Romney claimed Obama's domestic policies were ineffective and financially insolvent while Obama's campaign sought to characterize Romney as a plutocratic businessman who was out of touch with the average American.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The campaign was marked by a sharp rise in fundraising, including from nominally independent Super PACs.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Obama defeated Romney, winning 332 Electoral College votes and 51.1% of the popular vote to Romney's 206 electoral votes and 47.2% of the popular vote.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He became the third sitting president in a row (after Bill Clinton and George W.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Obama carried all 18 "blue wall" states and defeated Romney in crucial swing states that Republicans had previously won in 2000 and 2004, namely Colorado, Florida, Nevada, Ohio, and Virginia.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Despite his loss, Romney managed to flip Indiana, North Carolina, and Nebraska's 2nd congressional district from the 2008 election.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Ultimately, Obama won eight of the nine main swing states, losing only North Carolina.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Florida, Georgia, Ohio, Tennessee, and West Virginia's state legislatures approved measures to shorten early voting periods.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Florida and Iowa barred all felons from voting.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kansas, South Carolina, Tennessee, Texas, and Wisconsin state legislatures passed laws requiring voters to have government-issued IDs before they could cast their ballots.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This meant typically that people without driver's licenses or passports had to gain new forms of ID.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Former president Bill Clinton denounced them, saying, "There has never been in my lifetime, since we got rid of the poll tax and all the Jim Crow burdens on voting, the determined effort to limit the franchise that we see today".
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He was referring to Jim Crow laws passed in southern states near the turn of the twentieth century that disenfranchised most blacks from voting and excluded them from the political process for more than six decades.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Clinton said the moves would effectively disenfranchise core voter blocs that trend liberal, including college students, black people, and Latinos.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Obama campaign fought against the Ohio law, pushing for a petition and statewide referendum to repeal it in time for the 2012 election.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In addition, the Pennsylvania legislature proposed a plan to change its representation in the electoral college from the traditional winner-take-all model to a district-by-district model.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] As the governorship and both houses of its legislature were Republican-controlled, the move was viewed by some as an attempt to reduce Democratic chances.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Ultimately, they did not do it, leaving their winner take all format intact as of 2020.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] With an incumbent president running for re-election against token opposition, the race for the Democratic nomination was largely uneventful.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The nomination process consisted of primaries and caucuses, held by the 50 states, as well as Guam, Puerto Rico, Washington, D.C., U.S.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Virgin Islands, American Samoa, and Democrats Abroad.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Additionally, high-ranking party members known as superdelegates each received one vote in the convention.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A few of the primary challengers surpassed the president's vote total in individual counties in several of the seven contested primaries, though none made a significant impact in the delegate count.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Running unopposed everywhere else, Obama cemented his status as the Democratic presumptive nominee on April 3, 2012, by securing the minimum number of pledged delegates needed to obtain the nomination.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The first debate took place on May 5, 2011, in Greenville, South Carolina, with businessman Herman Cain, former New Mexico governor Gary Johnson, Ron Paul, Tim Pawlenty, and former Pennsylvania senator Rick Santorum participating.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Another debate took place a month later, with Newt Gingrich, Mitt Romney, former Utah governor Jon Huntsman, and Minnesota congresswoman Michele Bachmann participating, and Gary Johnson excluded.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A total of thirteen debates were held before the Iowa caucuses.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The first major event of the campaign was the Ames Straw Poll, which took place in Iowa on August 13, 2011.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Michele Bachmann won the straw poll (this ultimately proved to be the acme of her campaign).
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Pawlenty withdrew from the race after a poor showing in the straw poll, as did Thaddeus McCotter, the only candidate among those who qualified for the ballot who was refused entrance into the debate.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It became clear at around this point in the nomination process that while Romney was considered to be the likely nominee by the Republican establishment, a large segment of the conservative primary electorate found him to be too moderate for their political views.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Perry did poorly in the debates, however, and Herman Cain and then Newt Gingrich came to the fore in October and November.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Due to a number of scandals, Cain withdrew just before the end of the year, after having ballot placement in several states.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Around the same time, Johnson, who had been able to get into only one other debate, withdrew to seek the Libertarian Party nomination.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] For the first time in modern Republican Party history, three different candidates won the first three state contests in January (the Iowa caucuses, the New Hampshire primary, and the South Carolina primary).
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The election of county delegates at the caucuses would eventually lead to Ron Paul earning 22 of the 28 Iowa delegates to the Republican National Convention.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Newt Gingrich won South Carolina by a surprisingly large margin, and Romney won only in New Hampshire.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A number of candidates dropped out at this point in the nomination process.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bachmann withdrew after finishing sixth in the Iowa caucuses, Huntsman withdrew after coming in third in New Hampshire, and Perry withdrew when polls showed him drawing low numbers in South Carolina.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Santorum, who had previously run an essentially one-state campaign in Iowa, was able to organize a national campaign after his surprising victory there.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He unexpectedly carried three states in a row on February 7 and overtook Romney in nationwide opinion polls, becoming the only candidate in the race to effectively challenge the notion that Romney was the inevitable nominee.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, Romney won all of the other contests between South Carolina and the Super Tuesday primaries, and regained his first-place status in nationwide opinion polls by the end of February.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Super Tuesday primaries took place on March 6.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Romney carried six states, Santorum carried three, and Gingrich won only in his home state of Georgia.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Throughout the rest of March, 266 delegates were allocated in 12 events, including the territorial contests and the first local conventions that allocated delegates (Wyoming's county conventions).
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Santorum won Kansas and three Southern primaries, but he was unable to make any substantial gain on Romney, who became a formidable frontrunner after securing more than half of the delegates allocated in March.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After disappointing results in the April 24 primaries (finishing second in one state, third in three, and fourth in one), Gingrich dropped out on May 2 in a move that was seen as an effective end to the contest for the nomination.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After Gingrich's spokesman announced his upcoming withdrawal, the Republican National Committee declared Romney the party's presumptive nominee.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Ron Paul officially remained in the race, but he stopped campaigning on May 14 to focus on state conventions.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On May 29, after winning the Texas primary, Romney had received a sufficient number of delegates to clinch the party's nomination with the inclusion of unpledged delegates.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After winning the June 5 primaries in California and several other states, Romney had received more than enough pledged delegates to clinch the nomination without counting unpledged delegates, making the June 26 Utah Primary, the last contest of the cycle, purely symbolic.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] CNN's final delegate estimate, released on July 27, 2012, put Romney at 1,462 pledged delegates and 62 unpledged delegates, for a total estimate of 1,524 delegates.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] No other candidate had unpledged delegates.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The delegate estimates for the other candidates were Santorum at 261 delegates, Paul at 154, Gingrich at 142, Bachmann at 1, Huntsman at 1, and all others at 0.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On August 28, 2012, delegates at the Republican National Convention officially named Romney the party's presidential nominee.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Romney formally accepted the delegates' nomination on August 30, 2012.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Four other parties nominated candidates that had ballot access or write-in access to at least 270 electoral votes, the minimum number of votes needed in the 2012 election to win the presidency through a majority of the electoral college.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Candidates in bold were on ballots representing 270 electoral votes.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] All other candidates were on the ballots of fewer than 10 states, 100 electors, and less than 20% of voters nationwide.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The United States presidential election of 2012 broke new records in financing, fundraising, and negative campaigning.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Through grassroots campaign contributions, online donations, and Super PACs, Obama and Romney raised a combined total of more than $2 billion.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Super PACs constituted nearly one-fourth of the total financing, with most coming from pro-Romney PACs.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Obama raised $690 million through online channels, beating his record of $500 million in 2008.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Most of the advertising in the 2012 presidential campaign was decidedly negative—80% of Obama's ads and 84% of Romney's ads were negative.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The tax-exempt non-profit Americans for Prosperity, a so-called "outside group", that is, a political advocacy group that is not a political action committee or super-PAC, ran a television advertising campaign opposing Obama described by *The Washington Post* as "early and relentless".
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Commission on Presidential Debates held four debates during the last weeks of the campaign: three presidential and one vice-presidential.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The major issues debated were the economy and jobs, the federal budget deficit, taxation and spending, the future of Social Security, Medicare, and Medicaid, healthcare reform, education, social issues, immigration, and foreign policy.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] An independent presidential debate featuring minor party candidates took place on Tuesday, October 23 at the Hilton Hotel in Chicago, Illinois.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The debate was moderated by Larry King and organized by the Free & Equal Elections Foundation.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The participants were Gary Johnson (Libertarian), Jill Stein (Green), Virgil Goode (Constitution), and Rocky Anderson (Justice).
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A second debate between Stein and Johnson took place on Sunday, November 4, and was moderated by Ralph Nader.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Below is a list of states considered by one or more forecast to be competitive; states that are deemed to be "safe" or "solid" by forecasters *RealClearPolitics*, *Sabato's Crystal Ball*, and *FiveThirtyEight*.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On the day of the election, spread betting firm Spreadex offered an Obama Electoral College Votes spread of 296–300 to Romney's 239–243.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In fact Obama's victory over Romney was greater, winning 332 electoral votes to Romney's 206.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Obama received 51 percent of the national popular vote to Romney's 47 percent and carried eight of the nine states considered to be electoral battlegrounds.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Altogether, Obama won in 26 states plus the District of Columbia, while Romney carried 24 states.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Of the 3,154 counties/districts/independent cities making returns, Romney won the most popular votes in 2,447 (77.58%) while Obama carried 707 (22.42%).
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The results of the electoral vote were certified by Congress on January 4, 2013.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Popular vote totals are from the Federal Election Commission report.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The table below displays the official vote tallies by each state's Electoral College voting method.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The source for the results of all states, except those that amended their official results, is the official Federal Election Commission report.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The column labeled "Margin" shows Obama's margin of victory over Romney (the margin is negative for every state that Romney won).
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Maine and Nebraska each allow for their election results votes to be split between candidates.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The winner within each congressional district gets one electoral vote for the district.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The winner of the statewide vote gets two additional electoral votes.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the 2012 election, all four of Maine's electoral votes were won by Obama and all five of Nebraska's electoral votes were won by Romney.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After the networks called Ohio for Obama at around 11:15 pm EST on Election Day, Romney was ready to concede the race, but hesitated when Karl Rove strenuously objected on Fox News to the network's decision to make that call.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Ohio was arguably the most critical state for Romney, as no Republican has ever won the presidency without carrying it, as of 2026.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Romney campaign had already set up a transition website, and had scheduled and purchased a fireworks display to celebrate in case he won the election.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On November 30, 2012, it was revealed that shortly before the election, internal polling done by the Romney campaign had shown Romney ahead in Colorado and New Hampshire, tied in Iowa, and within a few points of Obama in Wisconsin, Pennsylvania, Minnesota, and Ohio.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In addition, the Romney campaign had assumed that they would win Florida, North Carolina and Virginia.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The polls had made Romney and his campaign team so confident of their victory that Romney did not write a concession speech until Obama's victory was announced.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Foreign leaders reacted with both positive and mixed messages.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Most world leaders congratulated and praised Obama on his re-election victory.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, Venezuela and some other states had tempered reactions.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Pakistan commented that Romney's defeat had made Pakistan-United States relations safer.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Stock markets fell noticeably after Obama's re-election, with the Dow Jones Industrial Average, NASDAQ, and the S&P 500 each declining over two percent the day after the election.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] All 50 states had a petition on the White House website We The People calling for their state to secede from the union.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] These petitions were created by individual people, with some gaining thousands of signatures.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The United States has a population of 50 million Hispanic and Latino Americans, 27 million of whom are citizens eligible to vote (13% of total eligible voters).
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Exit polls were conducted by Edison Research of Somerville, New Jersey, for the National Election Pool, a consortium which at the time consisted of ABC News, Associated Press, CBS News, CNN, Fox News, and NBC News.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Combined with the re-election victories of his two immediate predecessors, Bill Clinton in 1996 and George W.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Bush in 2004, Obama's re-election victory in 2012 marked only the second time in American history that three consecutive incumbent presidents were each won re-elections to their second terms.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This was also the first election since 1928 in which neither major-party ticket featured a presidential or vice presidential candidate with any military experience.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The election was arguably decided by three counties: Miami-Dade County (Florida); Cuyahoga County (Ohio) and Philadelphia (Pennsylvania).
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] If these three counties had cast zero votes, Obama would have lost all three states and the election.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This election marked the first time since Franklin D.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Roosevelt's last two re-elections in 1940 and 1944 that the Democratic nominee won a majority of the popular vote (as opposed to a plurality) in two consecutive elections.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Obama also became the first president of either party to secure a majority of the popular vote in two consecutive elections since Ronald Reagan in 1980 and 1984.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Obama is the third Democratic president to secure at least 51% of the vote twice, after Andrew Jackson and Franklin D.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Romney won the popular vote in 226 congressional districts making this the first time since 1960 that the winner of the election did not win the popular vote in a majority of the congressional districts.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This is the last time that the Democratic nominee won a majority of states in a presidential election.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Romney lost his home state of Massachusetts, becoming the first major party presidential candidate to lose his home state since Democrat Al Gore lost his home state of Tennessee to Republican George W.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Romney lost his home state by more than 23%, the worst losing margin for a major party candidate since John Frémont in 1856.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Even worse than Frémont, Romney failed to win a single county in his home state, something last seen by Theodore Roosevelt in 1912.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In addition, since Obama carried Ryan's home state of Wisconsin, the Romney–Ryan ticket was the first major party ticket since 1972 to have both of its nominees lose their home states.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Romney won the popular vote in every county of three states: Utah, Oklahoma, and West Virginia; Obama did so in four states: Vermont, Massachusetts, Rhode Island, and Hawaii.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Romney's loss prompted the Republican National Committee to try to appeal to the American Latino population by concentrating on different approaches to immigration.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] These were short-lived due to activity and anger from the Republican base and may have contributed to the selection of Donald Trump as their party's presidential nominee four years later.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Gary Johnson's popular vote total set a Libertarian Party record, and his popular vote percentage was the second-best showing for a Libertarian in a presidential election, trailing only Ed Clark's in 1980.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Johnson would go on to beat this record in the 2016 presidential election, winning the most votes for the Libertarian ticket in history.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] At the time, Green Party candidate Jill Stein's popular vote total made her the most successful female presidential candidate in a general election in United States history.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This was later surpassed by Hillary Clinton in 2016.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Obama is the fifth Democrat to have won re-election to a consecutive term, along with Andrew Jackson, Woodrow Wilson, Franklin D.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This presidential election was the most recent in which no state split its electoral votes, and the most recent in which a candidate received over 60% of the Electoral College vote.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This is the most recent election in which two major party nominees would go on to become president (namely, Obama and Biden).
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Obama's vote total was the fourth most votes received (behind Obama's 2008 victory and both major candidates in 2020) prior to 2024 and the most ever for a re-elected incumbent president.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] The election marked the first time since 1988 in which no state was won by a candidate with a plurality of the state's popular vote.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Furthermore, it is the only post-World War II presidential election in which no states were won by margins smaller than 30,000 votes.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Obama's narrowest victories were in New Hampshire by 39,643 votes, followed by Florida by 74,309 votes.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Every other presidential election in modern history has seen states narrowly won by several thousand votes.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] As of 2026, this is also the most recent election in which both all of Maine and Nebraska's electoral votes were won by one candidate.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] So far, this is the only presidential election in history where both the Republican and Democratic vice presidential candidates are practicing Roman Catholics.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] It is also the only presidential election where there are no white Protestants on a major party ticket.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] As of 2026, Obama is the most recent incumbent president to win a second consecutive term, and this is also the most recent election where any major party won consecutive elections.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Obama was the first Democrat since Franklin D.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Roosevelt to win a majority of the popular vote more than once.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] While Obama was the first president since Dwight D.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Eisenhower in 1952 and 1956 to receive more than 51% of the popular vote twice, he was also the first president since Franklin D.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Roosevelt in 1936, 1940, and 1944 to win consecutive presidential elections with declining percentages of the popular vote.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Obama was the most recent of just four presidents in United States history to win re-election with a lower percentage of the electoral vote than in their prior elections, the other three were James Madison in 1812, Woodrow Wilson in 1916 and Franklin D.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Additionally, Obama was the fifth of only five presidents to win re-election with a smaller percentage of the popular vote than in prior elections, the other four are James Madison in 1812, Andrew Jackson in 1832, Grover Cleveland in 1892, and Franklin D.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] All four major candidates for president and vice president went on to hold significant public office after this election.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Obama and Biden served their second terms as president and vice president, respectively.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Biden initially retired from politics after leaving office, but later was elected president in 2020, defeating Trump, and served one term.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Romney moved to Utah in 2014 and was elected to the Senate there in 2018, succeeding Orrin Hatch, and served one term.
[src:african-americans/2012-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Ryan served three more terms in the House and eventually served as Speaker from 2015 until his retirement from politics in 2019.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The **2020 United States census** was the 24th decennial United States census.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Census Day, the reference day used for the census, was April 1, 2020.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Other than a pilot study during the 2000 census, this was the first U.S. census to offer options to respond online or by phone, in addition to the paper response form used for previous censuses.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The census was taken during the COVID-19 pandemic, which affected its administration.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The census recorded a resident population of 331,449,281 in the 50 states and the national capital of Washington, D.C., reflecting an increase of 7.4%, or 22,703,743, over 2010.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The growth rate was the second-lowest ever recorded, and the net increase was the sixth-highest in history.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] This was the first census where the ten most-populous states each surpassed ten million residents, and the first census where the ten most-populous cities each surpassed one million residents.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] This census's data determined the electoral votes' distribution for the 2024 United States presidential election.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] As required by the United States Constitution, the U.S. census has been conducted every 10 years since 1790.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The 2010 United States census was the previous census completed.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] 18 and older are legally obligated to answer census questions, and to do so truthfully (Title 13 of the United States Code).
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Personally identifiable information is private and the Census Bureau itself will never release it.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] However, the National Archives and Records Administration could release the original census returns in 2092, if the 72-year rule is not changed before then.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] On census reference day, April 1, 2020, the resident United States population (50 states and Washington, D.C., excluding overseas territories and military members and civilian U.S. citizens living abroad) was projected to be 329.59 million, a 6.76% increase from the 2010 census.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The results of the 2020 census determine the number of seats for each state in the House of Representatives, hence also the number of electors for each state in the Electoral College, for elections from 2022 to 2032.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The Census Bureau announced the apportionment figures on April 26, 2021.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] This represented a smaller number of seats shifting than was forecast by independent analysts.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] State and local officials use censuses to redraw boundaries for districts such as congressional districts (redistricting), state legislative districts, and school districts.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Dozens of federal programs use census data to help direct funding to state and local areas.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Census results help determine how more than $675 billion in federal funding are allocated to states and communities each year for roads, schools, hospitals (health clinics), emergency services, and more.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The 2020 census was the first U.S. census to offer a full internet response option and the first to extensively use technology instead of paper to manage and conduct fieldwork.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Census Bureau submitted a list of questions to Congress on March 29, 2018.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The U.S. census will not share any participant's information with any government agency, as it is prohibited by Title 13 United States code.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] It has been challenged, but the Supreme Court has always prevailed in reference to Title 13 to protect the confidentiality and privacy of information provided.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Used to produce statistics about homeownership and renters for economic indicators, housing programs and informing planning decisions.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The sex of each person in the household.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Used to produce statistics used to plan and fund government programs, enforce laws, regulations, and policies against discrimination.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The age of each person in the household.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Used to better understand the size and characteristics of different age groups.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Agencies use these data to plan and fund government programs that support specific age groups, including children and older populations.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The race of each person in the household.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Used by federal agencies to monitor compliance with anti-discrimination provisions, such as those under the Voting Rights Act and the Civil Rights Act.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Whether a person in the household is of Hispanic, Latino, or Spanish origin.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The relationship of each person in the household to each other.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Used to plan and fund government programs that support families, including people raising children alone and other households who qualify for additional assistance.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The United States Census Bureau proposed but then withdrew plans to add a new category to classify Middle Eastern and North African peoples, over a dispute over whether this classification should be considered a white ethnicity or a separate race.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] According to the Census Bureau, 60.0% of all U.S. households had submitted their census questionnaire by May 22, 2020 –either online, by mail or by phone.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Most U.S. households were mailed an invitation letter between March 12–20 to self-respond.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] They account for more than 95% of all U.S. households.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Prior to the ongoing coronavirus pandemic, the remaining 5% of U.S. households (mostly in rural areas) were supposed to be visited by census takers in April/May, dropping off invitation letters to owners.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] This was delayed, but most census offices restarted work again in mid-May.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] In an update published October 19, 2020, the Census Bureau stated 99.98% of addresses had been accounted for, with all but one state over a 99.9% rate.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Paper responses postmarked on or before October 15 would be processed, as long as they arrived at the processing center by October 22.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] As in previous censuses, the 2020 census relied on a network of trusted voices nationwide to help raise awareness, answer questions, and encourage communities to participate.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Hundreds of local "complete count committees" are dedicating resources to the efforts nationwide.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] VMLY&R (formerly Young & Rubicam) secured the Integrated Communications Contract for the 2020 census campaign in August 2016.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] As the contract's primary agency of record, VMLY&R created an integrated team for this project, Team Y&R, which includes subcontractors specializing in minority outreach, digital media, earned media and more.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] In March 2019, the campaign unveiled the 2020 census tagline: "Shape your future.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] START HERE." The tagline was based on research that demonstrated which types of messages will reach and motivate all populations, including segments of the population who are historically hard to count.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The printing company Cenveo won the $61 million contract in October 2017 to produce census forms and reminders but went bankrupt less than four months later.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Government Publishing Office said the agency failed to check the company's financial status and improperly allowed the company to lower its bid after other bids were unsealed.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The coronavirus pandemic caused delays to census field operations and counts of the homeless and people living in group quarters.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] As of April 1, 2020, Census Day, the Census Bureau still planned to complete the count by the end of the year.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Census Bureau issued a press release by Director Steven Dillingham announcing that 2020 census field operations would be suspended for two weeks until April 1, 2020, due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] On March 27, 2020, the agency announced it would temporarily suspend in-person interviews for its on-going surveys.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The agency claimed that staffing adjustments at its call centers due to implementing health guidance had "led to increases in call wait times, affecting different languages at different times".
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] According to its own documentation, the U.S.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Census Bureau continued to pay 2020 census employees even though field operations were supposed to be suspended.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Census Bureau issued another press release announcing 2020 census field operations would be suspended for an additional two weeks, through April 15, 2020.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The agency announced on April 10, 2020, that it took steps to make "more employees available to respond to requests" at the call centers.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] In a joint statement on April 13, 2020, U.S.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Department of Commerce secretary Wilbur Ross and U.S.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Census Bureau director Steven Dillingham announced further operational adjustments to the 2020 census due to COVID-19 health and safety concerns.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Census Bureau director Steven Dillingham wrote to Department of Commerce inspector general Peggy E.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Gustafson responding to a March 12, 2020, memo sent by the Office of the Inspector General requesting information about the Census Bureau's plans to respond to the COVID-19 emergency by March 20, 2020.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The inspector general's memo asked how the Bureau would address staff and enumerator safety.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] To ensure the completeness and accuracy of the 2020 census, the Census Bureau is seeking statutory relief from Congress of 120 additional calendar days to deliver final apportionment counts.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] On April 24, 2020, Dillingham and other Census Bureau officials briefed the House Committee on Oversight and Reform on the agency's response to the COVID-19 emergency.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] This briefing came after many requests from the committee since March 12, 2020, including a last-minute cancellation on April 20, 2020.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] However, the National Processing Center and Area Census Offices had remained open.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Census Bureau began publishing dates as it claimed to begin a "phased restart of some 2020 census field operations in select geographic areas" and said they had "ordered personal protective equipment (PPE) for all field staff, including those that work in a field office.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The agency decided that face shields were necessary to protect employees from COVID-19 exposure, but provided them only to personnel at the headquarters and national processing centers.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Additional "restart" dates starting May 18 were published on May 15, 2020, for other geographic areas in eleven states.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] An OSHA complaint was recorded that same day from St.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Louis, that desks remained close together with no physical dividers, improper sanitation practices were being used, and no remote work for high-risk employees.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Louis Area Census Office was May 11, 2020.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] On May 21, 2020, procurement information for two contracts was entered into the Federal Procurement Data System.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] A press release on May 22, 2020, announced May 25 "restart" dates for ten more states.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] An OSHA complaint was made from Concord, California, on April 3, 2020, that there were at least two confirmed cases of COVID-19 unrecorded on OSHA 300 logs and that employees were working in close quarters with no disinfection of shared equipment such as headsets, laptops, and tablets.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The published restart date for the Concord, California, Area Census Office was May 25, 2020.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Offices were reopened in the areas of "American Samoa, the Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands, Guam and the U.S.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Virgin Islands in preparation for resuming operations for the 2020 Island Areas Censuses" on May 22, 2020.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] On May 29, 2020, a press release was published announcing "restart" of operations in seven additional states and the Washington, D.C., area starting from the week of June 1.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] In a June 5, 2020, press release, the U.S.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Days later, the Navajo Nation began reinstating lockdown restrictions and curfews due to a surge in new cases.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] A June 12, 2020, press release shared that the update leave (UL) operation had resumed, as well as fingerprinting of selected applicants.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] On August 3, 2020, the Census Bureau announced that field collection would end on September 30, rather than October 31 as planned in April.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Zabarsky, Principal Assistant Inspector General for Audit and Evaluation published an alert on behalf of the Department of Commerce Office of Inspector General, which stated that the number of COVID-19 related safety issues raised by hotline complaints tripled between July 1 and August 21.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The U.S. decennial census is used to determine federal funds, grants, and support to states.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The Census Bureau had included a citizenship question until 1950 when it was removed, though it continued to include a question asking about place of birth.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Ross was accused by Democrats in Congress of lying that the citizenship question was requested by the Justice Department and approved by him.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Upon the bureau's announcement, several state and city officials criticized the decision, reiterating the concern about discouraging participation from immigrants, resulting in undercounting, and questioning the motives of Secretary Ross in adding the question.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Three simultaneous separate federal lawsuits came out of this discovery, occurring at the district courts of New York, Maryland, and California.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] During these trials, documents released in May 2019 showed that the late Thomas B.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Hofeller, an architect of Republican gerrymandering, had found that adding the census question could help to gerrymander maps that "would be advantageous to Republicans and non-Hispanic whites".
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Hofeller later wrote the DOJ letter which justified the policy by claiming it was needed to enforce the 1965 Voting Rights Act.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The Trump administration on June 12, 2019, asserted executive privilege over portions of the requested documents.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] As a result, the House committee subsequently voted along party lines to hold both Ross and Barr in contempt that day.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The full House voted to hold Ross and Barr in contempt on July 17, 2019, in a 230–198 vote along party lines.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] A lawsuit, led by New York state's attorney general Barbara Underwood and joined by seventeen other states, fifteen cities and other civil rights groups, was filed in the United States District Court for the Southern District of New York.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] During the discovery phase of the trial, new information came to light that Ross had had previous discussions with Steve Bannon before March 2018 with the intent to add the citizenship question, contradicting statements he had made to Congress in March.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Furman in September 2018 to ask that Ross clear a day in his schedule to give a deposition to the court related to the addition of the census question prior to the planned start of the trial in November.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The Trump administration filed a writ of *mandamus* to the United States Supreme Court, requesting that they postpone the trial, and also to defer any involvement with Ross until the start of the trial.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The Supreme Court issued an order that allowed the trial *United States Census Bureau v.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] State of New York* to go forward, but agreed to postpone Ross's deposition until after the start of the trial.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The Supreme Court accepted the petition related to Furman's ruling on February 15, 2019, a separate matter from the question of Ross's deposition, and the case's oral arguments were heard on April 23, 2019.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The Supreme Court issued its decision on June 27, 2019, rejecting the Trump administration's stated rationale for including the question.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] While the Court majority agreed that the question was allowable under the Enumeration Act, they also agreed with the ability of the District Court to ask Commerce for further explanation for the question under the Administrative Procedure Act (APA).
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] They also agreed that the answers Commerce had provided at the time appeared to be "contrived" and pretextual, leaving open the possibility that Commerce could offer a better rationale.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The case was remanded back to the District Court, to allow Commerce to provide a better explanation for the rationale of the question to the District Court, who would deem if that was sufficient before allowing the question on the census.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The question would be allowed on the census only if these steps can be completed before the self-imposed form printing deadline.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) has taken steps to introduce the Hofeller evidence into the New York case but it will not be heard until late 2019 after the census forms are to be published.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The second suit over the census question came in the United States District Court for the Northern District of California under Judge Richard Seeborg, raised by the state of California and several cities within it.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] In March 2019, Seeborg similarly found as Furman had in New York that the addition of the census question was unconstitutional and issued an injunction to block its use.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The government appealed to the Ninth Circuit before the Supreme Court remanded the case.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] A similar question related to the intent of the question was raised by several immigrants-rights groups in the United States District Court for the District of Maryland.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The case was overseen by Judge George J.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Hazel had found for the pro-immigration groups in April 2019, ruling that the addition of an immigration question to the census was unconstitutional.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The government issued its appeal to the Fourth Circuit Court of Appeals.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The new Hofeller evidence was presented to Hazel as the case was being heard on appeal during June 2019 at the Fourth Circuit.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Hazel said the new evidence "raises a substantial issue".
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] On June 25, 2019, the Fourth Circuit remanded the case back to Hazel's District Court with the newly provided evidence, and to review if the additional evidence showed discriminatory intent.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Should Hazel find such intent, it would be possible for him to place an injunction on the addition of the census question during a new discovery phase, regardless of the Supreme Court decision in *Department of Commerce v.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] This action would effectively render the question moot since the census forms would need to be published at this point without the citizenship question to meet the mailing deadlines.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] President Trump, after the Supreme Court decision in *Department of Commerce* was announced, stated his intent to find a way to delay the census as long as possible so the judicial matter could be resolved.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] On July 2, 2019, the Department of Justice (DOJ) announced that the citizenship question would not be included in the census, and the Commerce Department began printing census forms without a citizenship question.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] However, the next day, Trump insisted his administration was "absolutely moving forward" with the citizenship question, and the Justice Department confirmed in court that it had been instructed to find a legal way to include it in the census.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] In response to an order from Judge Hazel, the Justice Department affirmed on July 5, 2019, that it will be seeking a route to add the citizenship question to the census, though at the time did not know which route it would take.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Hazel had ordered this response as, if the department was intending to add the question, he could begin determining a schedule in coordination with Judge Furman in the New York court for further proceedings and discovery in both the New York and the Maryland lawsuits.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Furman pointed out that the case had already run past the DOJ's own previously requested deadline of July 1 and replacing counsel would cause further delays.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Separate from the events in the courts, Trump has said he also considered using an executive order to place the citizenship question on the census.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] However, on July 11 he issued Executive Order 13880 directing the Department of Commerce to obtain citizenship data from other federal agencies rather than via the census.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] He added that "we are not backing down in our effort to determine the citizenship status of the United States population" and that data from other federal agencies would be "far more accurate" than a census question.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Accordingly, the department will promptly inform the courts that the government will not include a citizenship question on the 2020 decennial census." Besides federal agencies, the Department of Commerce is obtaining citizenship data from state records.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Joe Biden, on his first day of his presidency on January 20, 2021, issued an executive order that revoked both Trump's July 11 executive order and Trump's July 21 memo, as to have the census follow the standard practice of including the counts of undocumented immigrants within the final numbers.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The order did not rescind a directive for the Census Bureau to use government records to produce block-level citizenship data.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The state believed it would lose a congressional seat to other states that have had increased numbers of immigrants in the last decade.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The motion was granted by the end of 2018.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] As the census question case continued, the Census Bureau spoke of other means to obtain immigration data, and Barr, referencing the Alabama suit, said that "for example, there is a current dispute over whether illegal aliens can be included for apportionment purposes.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Depending on the resolution of that dispute, this data may be relevant to those considerations.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] We will be studying this issue." Spurred by Barr's comments that the government would not defend itself in the case, a coalition of fifteen states and other groups also moved to intervene, which was granted by September 2019.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] On July 21, 2020, President Trump signed a memo to the Department of Commerce, "Memorandum on Excluding Illegal Aliens from the Apportionment Base Following the 2020 Census" with instructions not to include illegal immigrants in the census totals for purposes of apportionment.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The memo said the Constitution does not define which "persons" must be included in the apportionment base, and past censuses have excluded some legal immigrants in the country temporarily, justifying the change.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Law and census experts said this was an invalid interpretation as past case law has supported inclusion of "whole persons" including illegal immigrants, and the ACLU immediately said they planned to file a lawsuit against the administration over the memo.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Common Cause, the city of Atlanta, and other groups and individuals filed the first suit seeking an injunction to prevent the government from executing on the memo a week after it was signed in the United States District Court for the District of Columbia.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] On September 10, 2020, a three-judge panel of the United States District Court for the Southern District of New York unanimously rejected the order, ruling that it was so obviously illegal a lawsuit challenging it was unnecessary.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Eight days later, the Trump administration filed notice that it would appeal the decision directly to the Supreme Court, bypassing the circuit court appeals process.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The Supreme Court accepted the petition on October 16, 2020, and scheduled expedited oral arguments in the case on November 30, 2020.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The Court ruled in a *per curiam* decision on December 18, 2020, that the case was premature due to lack of standing and ripeness but did not rule on any of the constitutional challenges at the time.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The decision vacated the District Court's ruling and remanded the case to the District Court to be dismissed.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The Trump administration sought to complete the census count earlier than originally scheduled.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] In September 2020, federal district court judge Lucy Koh issued a preliminary injunction against the plan to end counting on September 30 rather than the scheduled October 31, saying the Commerce Department "never articulated a satisfactory explanation".
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] She also blocked a plan to deliver the count results to the White House by December 31, rather than the original April 2021 delivery date when Trump might be out of office.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] On the next business day, Commerce Secretary Wilbur Ross announced the count would end October 5, as the administration appealed Koh's decision to the ninth circuit.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Koh ordered the government to produce documents to show the Commerce Department's reasoning.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The appeals court upheld Koh's ruling, and the Census Bureau announced on October 2 that the count would continue until October 31.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Also on October 2, Koh threatened to hold Ross in contempt for repeated violations of her order.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The ninth circuit decision was appealed to the Supreme Court.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] On October 13, in a 7–1 ruling, the court issued an unsigned order granting the request to end the count early.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] As one of his first acts in office, President Joe Biden signed Executive Order 13986 on January 20, 2021, to discontinue citizenship tabulations at the city-block level using 2020 census data with administrative records.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] He also revoked a Trump directive that would have excluded those in the country illegally from the figures used for apportioning congressional seats among the states.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Researchers widely criticized the Census Bureau for intentionally making block-level data inaccurate by using differential privacy.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] In order to purportedly prevent identification of individuals' age, gender, race, household relationships, or homeownership, "disclosure avoidance noise" was added to the data, shifting individuals between blocks, towns, or other units.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] This can result in substantial discrepancies in minority populations and the sizes of small places.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] For example, Monowi, Nebraska, known for being the country's smallest incorporated municipality, was incorrectly reported to have two residents instead of one.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Redistricting data would also be corrupted, making equal-size districts and majority-minority districts more difficult.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] On March 10, 2022, the Census Bureau released estimates of total overcount and undercount by demographic characteristic.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] The results found that the total Hispanic population had likely been undercounted by 4.99%, the Black population by 3.3% and *Some other race* by 4.34%.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Asians were estimated to have been overcounted by 2.62%, Non-Hispanic Whites by 1.64%, and Pacific Islanders by 1.28%.
[src:african-americans/2020-united-states-census] Native Americans were estimated to have been undercounted by 0.91%; however, those living on reservations were undercounted by 5.64%, while those living elsewhere were overcounted by 3.06%.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] African-American history began in the 16th century, when mainly West African and Central African slave traders sold African artisans, farmers, and warriors to European slave traders, who transported them across the Atlantic to the Western Hemisphere.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] They were sold as slaves to European colonists and put to work on plantations, particularly in the southern colonies.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] A few were able to achieve freedom through manumission or escape, and founded independent communities before and during the American Revolution.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] After the United States was founded in 1783, most American Black people continued to be enslaved, primarily in the American South, with four million enslaved people only liberated after the Northern victory over the South in the Civil War of 1861 to 1865.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] During Reconstruction, African Americans gained citizenship and adult-males the right to vote; however, due to widespread belief in White supremacy, they were treated as second-class citizens and soon effectively disenfranchised in the South.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] These circumstances changed due to participation in the military conflicts of the United States, substantial migration out of the South, the elimination of legal racial segregation, and the civil rights movement which sought political and social freedom.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] However, racism against African Americans and racial socioeconomic disparity remain a problem into the 21st century.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] In the 20th and 21st centuries, immigration has played an increasingly significant role in the African-American community.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Black population were immigrants, and 20% were either immigrants or the children of immigrants.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] While some Black immigrants or their children may also come to identify as African American, the majority of first-generation immigrants do not, preferring to identify with their nation of origin.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Most African Americans are of West African and coastal Central African ancestry, with varying amounts of Western European and Native American ancestry (see §Genetics).
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] African-American culture has had a significant influence on worldwide culture, making numerous contributions to the English language, literature, politics, cuisine, sports, and music.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] The African-American contribution to popular music is so profound that most American popular music, including gospel, blues, jazz, rock and roll, R&B, soul, funk, disco, hip-hop, and house has its origins either partially or entirely in the African-American community.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] The vast majority of those who were enslaved and transported in the transatlantic slave trade were people from several Central and West African ethnic groups.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] They had been captured directly by European slave traders in coastal raids, or captured and sold by West African slave traders or by half-European "merchant princes" to European slave traders, who brought them to the Americas.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] The first African slaves in what is now the United States arrived in the early 16th century.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Africans were among Juan Ponce de León's 1513 voyage that landed in what would become Spanish Florida, and enslaved Africans arrived around the same time to Spanish Puerto Rico.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Africans also came via Santo Domingo in the Caribbean to the San Miguel de Gualdape colony (most likely located in the Winyah Bay area of present-day South Carolina), founded by Spanish explorer Lucas Vázquez de Ayllón in 1526.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] The ill-fated colony was almost immediately disrupted by a fight over leadership, during which the slaves revolted and fled the colony to seek refuge among local Native Americans.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] De Ayllón and many of the colonists died shortly afterward, due to an epidemic and the colony was abandoned.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] The settlers and the slaves who had not escaped returned to the Island of Hispaniola, whence they had come.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] The enslaved explorer Esteban arrived in Florida with the Narváez expedition in 1528, a journey that first landed in Santo Domingo and later traveled into Spanish Texas and the Southwest before ending in Mexico.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] The marriage between Luisa de Abrego, a free Black domestic servant from Seville, and Miguel Rodríguez, a White Segovian conquistador in 1565 in St.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Augustine (Spanish Florida), is the first known and recorded Christian marriage anywhere in what is now the continental United States.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] The first recorded Africans in English America (including most of the future United States) were "20 and odd negroes" who arrived in Jamestown, Virginia via Cape Comfort in August 1619 as indentured servants.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] As many Virginian settlers began to die from harsh conditions, more and more Africans were brought to work as laborers.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] An indentured servant (who could be White or Black) would work for several years (usually four to seven) without wages.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] The status of indentured servants in early Virginia and Maryland was similar to slavery.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Servants could be bought, sold, or leased, and they could be physically beaten for disobedience or attempting to running away.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Unlike slaves, they were freed after their term of service expired or if their freedom was purchased.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Their children did not inherit their status, and on their release from contract they received "a year's provision of corn, double apparel, tools necessary", and a small cash payment called "freedom dues".
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Africans could legally raise crops and cattle to purchase their freedom.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] They raised families, married other Africans and sometimes intermarried with Native Americans or European settlers.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] By the 1640s and 1650s, several African families owned farms around Jamestown, and some became wealthy by colonial standards and purchased indentured servants of their own.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] In 1640, the Virginia General Court recorded the earliest documentation of lifetime slavery when they sentenced John Punch, a Negro, to lifetime servitude under his master Hugh Gwyn, for running away.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] In Spanish Florida, some Spanish married or had unions with Pensacola, Creek or African women, both enslaved and free, and their descendants created a mixed-race population of mestizos and mulattos.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] The Spanish encouraged slaves from the colony of Georgia to come to Florida as a refuge, promising freedom in exchange for conversion to Catholicism.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] King Charles II issued a royal proclamation freeing all slaves who fled to Spanish Florida and accepted conversion and baptism.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Augustine, but escaped slaves also reached Pensacola.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Augustine had mustered an all-Black militia unit defending Spanish Florida as early as 1683.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] One of the Dutch African arrivals, Anthony Johnson, would later own one of the first Black "slaves", John Casor, resulting from the court ruling of a civil case.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] The popular conception of a race-based slave system did not fully develop until the 18th century.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] The Dutch West India Company introduced slavery in 1625 with the importation of eleven Black slaves into New Amsterdam (present-day New York City).
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] All the colony's slaves, however, were freed upon its surrender to the English.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Massachusetts was the first English colony to legally recognize slavery in 1641.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] In 1662, Virginia passed a law that children of enslaved women would take the status of the mother, rather than that of the father, as was the case under common law.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] This legal principle was called *partus sequitur ventrum*.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] By an act of 1699, Virginia ordered the deportation of all free Blacks, effectively defining all people of African descent who remained in the colony as slaves.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] In 1670, the colonial assembly passed a law prohibiting free and baptized Blacks (and Native Americans) from purchasing Christians (in this act meaning White Europeans) but allowing them to buy people "of their owne nation".
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] In Spanish Louisiana, although there was no movement toward abolition of the African slave trade, Spanish rule introduced a new law called *coartación*, which allowed slaves to buy their freedom, and that of others.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Although some did not have the money to do so, government measures on slavery enabled the existence of many free Blacks.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] This caused problems to the Spaniards with the French creoles (French who had settled in New France) who had also populated Spanish Louisiana.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] The French creoles cited that measure as one of the system's worst elements.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] First established in South Carolina in 1704, groups of armed White men—slave patrols—were formed to monitor enslaved Black people.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Their function was to police slaves, especially fugitives.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Slave owners feared that slaves might organize revolts or slave rebellions, so state militias were formed to provide a military command structure and discipline within the slave patrols.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] These patrols were used to detect, encounter, and crush any organized slave meetings which might lead to revolts or rebellions.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] The earliest African American congregations and churches were organized before 1800 in both northern and southern cities following the Great Awakening.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] By 1775, Africans made up 20% of the population in the American colonies, which made them the second-largest ethnic group after English Americans.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] During the 1770s, Africans, both enslaved and free, helped rebellious American colonists secure their independence by defeating the British in the American Revolutionary War.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Blacks played a role in both sides in the American Revolution.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Activists in the Patriot cause included James Armistead, Prince Whipple, and Oliver Cromwell.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Around 15,000 Black Loyalists left with the British after the war, most of them ending up as free Black people in England or its colonies, such as the Black Nova Scotians and the Sierra Leone Creole people.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] In the Spanish Louisiana, Governor Bernardo de Gálvez organized Spanish free Black men into two militia companies to defend New Orleans during the American Revolution.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] They fought in the 1779 battle in which Spain captured Baton Rouge from the British.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Gálvez also commanded them in campaigns against the British outposts in Mobile, Alabama, and Pensacola, Florida.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] He recruited slaves for the militia by pledging to free anyone who was seriously wounded and promised to secure a low price for *coartación* (buy their freedom and that of others) for those who received lesser wounds.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] During the 1790s, Governor Francisco Luis Héctor, baron of Carondelet reinforced local fortifications and recruit even more free Black men for the militia.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Carondelet doubled the number of free Black men who served, creating two more militia companies—one made up of Black members and the other of pardo (mixed race).
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Serving in the militia brought free Black men one step closer to equality with Whites, allowing them, for example, the right to carry arms and boosting their earning power.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] However, actually these privileges distanced free Black men from enslaved Blacks and encouraged them to identify with Whites.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Slavery had been tacitly enshrined in the US Constitution through provisions such as Article I, Section 2, Clause 3, commonly known as the 3/5 compromise.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Due to the restrictions of Section 9, Clause 1, Congress was unable to pass an Act Prohibiting Importation of Slaves until 1807.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Fugitive slave laws (derived from the Fugitive Slave Clause of the Constitution—Article IV, Section 2, Clause 3) were passed by Congress in both 1793 and 1850, guaranteeing the right of a slaveholder to recover an escaped slave anywhere within the US.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Slave owners, who viewed enslaved people as property, ensured that it became a federal crime to aid or assist those who had fled slavery or to interfere with their capture.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] By that time, slavery, which almost exclusively targeted Black people, had become the most critical and contentious political issue in the Antebellum United States, repeatedly sparking crises and conflicts.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Among these were the Missouri Compromise, the Compromise of 1850, the infamous Dred Scott decision, and John Brown's raid on Harpers Ferry.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Prior to the Civil War, eight serving presidents had owned slaves, a practice that was legally protected under the US Constitution.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] By 1860, the number of enslaved Black people in the US had grown to between 3.5 and 4.4 million, largely as a result of the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] In addition, 488,000–500,000 Black people lived free around the country, with legislated limits imposed upon them in addition to "unconquerable prejudice" from Whites according to Henry Clay.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] In response to these conditions, some free Black people chose to leave the US and emigrate to Liberia in West Africa.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Liberia had been established in 1821 as a settlement by the American Colonization Society (ACS), with many abolitionist members of the ACS believing Black Americans would have greater opportunities for freedom and equality in Africa than they would in the US.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Slaves not only represented a significant financial investment for their owners, but they also played a crucial role in producing the country's most valuable product and export: cotton.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Enslaved people were instrumental in the construction of several prominent structures such as, the United States Capitol, the White House and other Washington, D.C.–based buildings.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Similar building projects existed in the slave states.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] By 1815, the domestic slave trade had become a significant and major economic activity in the United States, continuing to flourish until the 1860s.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Historians estimate that nearly one million individuals were subjected to this forced migration, which was often referred to as a new "Middle Passage".
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] The historian Ira Berlin described this internal forced migration of enslaved people as the "central event" in the life of a slave during the period between the American Revolution and the Civil War.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Berlin emphasized that whether enslaved individuals were directly uprooted or lived in constant fear that they or their families would be involuntarily relocated, "the massive deportation traumatized Black people" throughout the US.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] As a result of this large-scale forced movement, countless individuals lost their connection to families and clans, and many ethnic Africans lost their knowledge of varying tribal origins in Africa.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Emigration of free Blacks to their continent of origin had been proposed since the Revolutionary war.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] After Haiti became independent, it tried to recruit African Americans to migrate there after it re-established trade relations with the United States.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] The Haitian Union was a group formed to promote relations between the countries.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] After riots against Blacks in Cincinnati, its Black community sponsored founding of the Wilberforce Colony, an initially successful settlement of African American immigrants to Canada.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] The colony was one of the first such independent political entities.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] It lasted for a number of decades and provided a destination for about 200 Black families emigrating from a number of locations in the United States.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] In 1863, during the American Civil War, President Abraham Lincoln signed the Emancipation Proclamation.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] The proclamation declared that all slaves in Confederate-held territory were free.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Advancing Union troops enforced the proclamation, with Texas being the last state to be emancipated, in 1865.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Slavery in a few border states continued until the ratification of the Thirteenth Amendment in December 1865.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] While the Naturalization Act of 1790 limited US citizenship to Whites only, the 14th Amendment (1868) gave Black people citizenship, and the 15th Amendment (1870) gave Black men the right to vote.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] African Americans quickly set up congregations for themselves, as well as schools and community/civic associations, to have space away from White control or oversight.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] While the post-war Reconstruction era was initially a time of progress for African Americans, that period ended in 1876.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] By the late 1890s, Southern states enacted Jim Crow laws to enforce racial segregation and disenfranchisement.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Segregation was now imposed with Jim Crow laws, using signs used to show Blacks where they could legally walk, talk, drink, rest, or eat.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] For those places that were racially mixed, non-Whites had to wait until all White customers were dealt with.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Most African Americans obeyed the Jim Crow laws, to avoid racially motivated violence.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] To maintain self-esteem and dignity, African Americans such as Anthony Overton and Mary McLeod Bethune continued to build their own schools, churches, banks, social clubs, and other businesses.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] In the last decade of the 19th century, racially discriminatory laws and racial violence aimed at African Americans began to mushroom in the United States, a period often referred to as the "nadir of American race relations".
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] These discriminatory acts included racial segregation—upheld by the United States Supreme Court decision in *Plessy v.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] The desperate conditions of African Americans in the South sparked the Great Migration during the first half of the 20th century which led to a growing African American community in Northern and Western United States.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] The rapid influx of Blacks disturbed the racial balance within Northern and Western cities, exacerbating hostility between both Blacks and Whites in the two regions.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] The Red Summer of 1919 was marked by hundreds of deaths and higher casualties across the US as a result of race riots that occurred in more than three dozen cities, such as the Chicago race riot of 1919 and the Omaha race riot of 1919.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Overall, Blacks in Northern and Western cities experienced systemic discrimination in a plethora of aspects of life.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Within employment, economic opportunities for Blacks were routed to the lowest-status and restrictive in potential mobility.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] While many Whites defended their space with violence, intimidation, or legal tactics toward African Americans, many other Whites migrated to more racially homogeneous suburban or exurban regions, a process known as White flight.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Despite discrimination, drawing cards for leaving the hopelessness in the South were the growth of African American institutions and communities in Northern cities.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Institutions included Black oriented organizations (e.g., Urban League, NAACP), churches, businesses, and newspapers, as well as successes in the development in African American intellectual culture, music, and popular culture (e.g., Harlem Renaissance, Chicago Black Renaissance).
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] The Cotton Club in Harlem was a Whites-only establishment, with Blacks (such as Duke Ellington) allowed to perform, but to a White audience.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Black Americans also found a new ground for political power in Northern cities, without the enforced disabilities of Jim Crow.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] By the 1950s, the civil rights movement was gaining momentum.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] A 1955 lynching that sparked public outrage about injustice was that of Emmett Till, a 14-year-old boy from Chicago.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Spending the summer with relatives in Money, Mississippi, Till was killed for allegedly having wolf-whistled at a White woman.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Till had been badly beaten, one of his eyes was gouged out, and he was shot in the head.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] The visceral response to his mother's decision to have an open-casket funeral mobilized the Black community throughout the US.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Vann Newkirk wrote "the trial of his killers became a pageant illuminating the tyranny of White supremacy".
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] The state of Mississippi tried two defendants, but they were speedily acquitted by an all-White jury.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] The March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom and the conditions which brought it into being are credited with putting pressure on presidents John F.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] By 1966, the emergence of the Black Power movement, which lasted from 1966 to 1975, expanded upon the aims of the civil rights movement to include economic and political self-sufficiency, and freedom from White authority.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] During the post-war period, many African Americans continued to be economically disadvantaged relative to other Americans.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Average Black income stood at 54 percent of that of White workers in 1947, and 55 percent in 1962.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] In 1965, 43 percent of all Black families fell into the poverty bracket, earning under $3,000 (equivalent to $30,649 in 2025) a year.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] The 1960s saw improvements in the social and economic conditions of many Black Americans.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] From 1965 to 1969, Black family income rose from 54 to 60 percent of White family income.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] In 1968, 23 percent of Black families earned under $3,000 (equivalent to $27,775 in 2025) a year, compared with 41 percent in 1960.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] In 1965, 19 percent of Black Americans had incomes equal to the national median, a proportion that rose to 27 percent by 1967.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] In 1960, the median level of education for Blacks had been 10.8 years, and by the late 1960s, the figure rose to 12.2 years, half a year behind the median for Whites.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Politically and economically, African Americans have made substantial strides during the post–civil rights era.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] In 1967, Thurgood Marshall became the first African American Supreme Court Justice.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] In 1968, Shirley Chisholm became the first Black woman elected to the US Congress.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] In 1989, Douglas Wilder became the first African American elected governor in US history.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Clarence Thomas succeeded Marshall to become the second African American Supreme Court Justice in 1991.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] In 1992, Carol Moseley-Braun of Illinois became the first African American woman elected to the US Senate.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] There were 8,936 Black officeholders in the United States in 2000, showing a net increase of 7,467 since 1970.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] In 2005, the number of Africans immigrating to the United States, in a single year, surpassed the peak number who were involuntarily brought to the United States during the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] On November 4, 2008, Democratic Senator Barack Obama—the son of a White American mother and a Kenyan father—defeated Republican Senator John McCain to become the first African American to be elected president.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] At least 95 percent of African American voters voted for Obama.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] He also received overwhelming support from young and educated Whites, a majority of Asians, and Hispanics, picking up a number of new states in the Democratic electoral column.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Obama lost the overall White vote, although he won a larger proportion of White votes than any previous non-incumbent Democratic presidential candidate since Jimmy Carter.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] Obama was reelected for a second and final term, by a similar margin on November 6, 2012.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] In 2021, Kamala Harris, the daughter of a Jamaican father and Indian mother, became the first woman, the first African American, and the first Asian American to serve as Vice President of the United States.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p01] In June 2021, Juneteenth, a day which commemorates the end of slavery in the US, became a federal holiday.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In 1790, when the first US census was taken, Africans (including slaves and free people) numbered about 760,000—about 19.3% of the population.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In 1860, at the start of the Civil War, the African American population had increased to 4.4 million, but the percentage rate dropped to 14% of the overall population of the country.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] The vast majority were slaves, with only 488,000 counted as "freemen".
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] By 1900, the Black population had doubled and reached 8.8 million.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In 1910, about 90% of African Americans lived in the South.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Large numbers began migrating north looking for better job opportunities and living conditions, and to escape Jim Crow laws and racial violence.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] The Great Migration, as it was called, spanned the 1890s to the 1970s.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] From 1916 through the 1960s, more than six million Black people moved north.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] But in the 1970s and 1980s, that trend reversed, with more African Americans moving south to the Sun Belt than leaving it.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] By 1990, the African American population reached about 30 million and represented 12% of the US population, roughly the same proportion as in 1900.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] At the time of the 2000 US census, 54.8% of African Americans lived in the South.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In that year, 17.6% of African Americans lived in the Northeast and 18.7% in the Midwest, while only 8.9% lived in the Western states.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] The west does have a sizable Black population in certain areas, however.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] California, the nation's most populous state, has the fifth-largest African American population, only behind New York, Texas, Georgia, and Florida.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] According to the 2000 census, approximately 2.05% of African Americans identified as Hispanic or Latino in origin, many of whom may be of Brazilian, Puerto Rican, Dominican, Cuban, Haitian, or other Latin American descent.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] The only self-reported *ancestral* groups larger than African Americans are the Irish and Germans.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] According to the 2010 census, nearly 3% of people who self-identified as Black had recent ancestors who immigrated from another country.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Self-reported non-Hispanic Black immigrants from the Caribbean, mostly from Jamaica and Haiti, represented 0.9% of the US population, at 2.6 million.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Self-reported Black immigrants from sub-Saharan Africa also represented 0.9%, at about 2.8 million.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Additionally, self-identified Black Hispanics represented 0.4% of the United States population, at about 1.2 million people, largely found within the Puerto Rican and Dominican communities.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Self-reported Black immigrants hailing from other countries in the Americas, such as Brazil and Canada, as well as several European countries, represented less than 0.1% of the population.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Mixed-race Hispanic and non-Hispanic Americans who identified as being part Black, represented 0.9% of the population.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Of the 12.6% of United States residents who identified as Black, around 10.3% were "native Black American" or ethnic African Americans, who are direct descendants of West/Central Africans brought to the US as slaves.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] These individuals make up well over 80% of all Blacks in the country.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] When including people of mixed-race origin, about 13.5% of the US population self-identified as Black or "mixed with Black".
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] However, according to the US Census Bureau, evidence from the 2000 census indicates that many African and Caribbean immigrant ethnic groups do not identify as "Black, African Am., or Negro".
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Instead, they wrote in their own respective ethnic groups in the "Some Other Race" write-in entry.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] As a result, the census bureau devised a new, separate "African American" ethnic group category in 2010 for ethnic African Americans.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Nigerian Americans and Ethiopian Americans were the most reported sub-Saharan African groups in the United States.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In the 2020 census, the African American population was undercounted at an estimated rate of 3.3%, up from 2.1% in 2010.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Texas has the largest African American population by state with approximately four million.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Followed by Texas is Florida, with 3.8 million, and Georgia, with 3.6 million.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Mississippi is the state with the highest African American share of the population at 39%.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Followed by Mississippi is Louisiana at 34%, and Georgia at 32%.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] After 100 years of African Americans leaving the south in large numbers seeking better opportunities and treatment in the west and north, a movement known as the Great Migration, there is now a reverse trend, called the New Great Migration.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] As with the earlier Great Migration, the New Great Migration is primarily directed toward cities and large urban areas, such as Charlotte, Houston, Dallas, Fort Worth, Huntsville, Raleigh, Tampa, San Antonio, New Orleans, Memphis, Nashville, Jacksonville, and so forth.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] A growing percentage of African Americans from the west and north are migrating to the southern region of the US for economic and cultural reasons.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In 2020, New York City, Chicago, and Los Angeles metropolitan areas had the highest decline in African Americans, while Atlanta, Dallas, and Houston had the highest increase respectively.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Despite recent declines, as of 2020, the New York City metropolitan area still has the largest African American metropolitan population in the United States and the only to have over three million African Americans.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Among cities of 100,000 or more, South Fulton, Georgia had the highest percentage of Black residents of any large US city in 2020, with 93%.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Claiborne County, Mississippi is the Blackest county in the U.S. at 87% Black in 2020.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Cook County, Illinois has the largest Black population in the U.S. with 1,185,601 Black residents in 2020.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] The nation's most affluent community with an African American majority resides in View Park–Windsor Hills, California, with an annual median household income of $159,618 and median home price of about $1.5 million in 2025.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Additionally, there is a significant affluent Black presence in the southern Chicago suburbs of Cook County, Illinois.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In 2006, Queens County, New York was the only county with a population of 65,000 or more where African Americans had a higher median household income than White Americans.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Seatack, Virginia is currently the oldest African American community in the United States.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] It survives today with a vibrant and active civic community.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] During slavery, anti-literacy laws were enacted in the US that prohibited education for Black people.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Slave owners saw literacy as a threat to the institution of slavery.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] When slavery was finally abolished in 1865, public educational systems were expanding across the country.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] By 1870, around seventy-four institutions in the south provided a form of advanced education for African American students.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] By 1900, over a hundred programs at these schools provided training for Black professionals, including teachers.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Many of the students at Fisk University, including the young W.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Du Bois, taught school during the summers to support their studies.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] African Americans were very concerned to provide quality education for their children, but White supremacy limited their ability to participate in educational policymaking on the political level.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] State governments soon moved to undermine their citizenship by restricting their right to vote.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] By the late 1870s, Blacks were disenfranchised and segregated across the American South.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] White politicians in Mississippi and other states withheld financial resources and supplies from Black schools.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Nevertheless, the presence of Black teachers, and their engagement with their communities both inside and outside the classroom, ensured that Black students had access to education despite these external constraints.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] During World War II, demands for unity and racial tolerance on the home front provided an opening for the first Black history curriculum in the country.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] For example, during the early 1940s, Madeline Morgan, a Black teacher in the Chicago public schools, created a curriculum for students in grades one through eight highlighting the contributions of Black people to the history of the United States.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] At the close of the war, Chicago's Board of Education downgraded the curriculum's status from mandatory to optional.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Predominantly Black schools for kindergarten through twelfth grade students were common throughout the US before the 1970s.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] By 1972, however, desegregation efforts meant that only 25% of Black students were in schools with more than 90% non-White students.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] However, since then, a trend towards re-segregation affected communities across the country: by 2011, 2.9 million African American students were in such overwhelmingly minority schools, including 53% of Black students in school districts that were formerly under desegregation orders.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] As late as 1947, about one third of African Americans over 65 were considered to lack the literacy to read and write their own names.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] By 1969, illiteracy as it had been traditionally defined, had been largely eradicated among younger African Americans.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Between 1995 and 2009, freshmen college enrollment for African Americans increased by 73 percent and only 15 percent for Whites.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Black women are enrolled in college more than any other race and gender group, leading all with 9.7% enrolled according to the 2011 US census.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] The average high school graduation rate of Blacks in the United States has steadily increased to 71% in 2013.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Separating this statistic into component parts shows it varies greatly depending upon the state and the school district examined.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] 38% of Black males graduated in the state of New York but in Maine 97% graduated and exceeded the White male graduation rate by 11 percentage points.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In much of the southeastern United States and some parts of the southwestern United States the graduation rate of White males was in fact below 70% such as in Florida where 62% of White males graduated from high school.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Examining specific school districts paints an even more complex picture.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In the Detroit school district, the graduation rate of Black males was 20% but 7% for White males.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In the New York City school district 28% of Black males graduate from high school compared to 57% of White males.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In Newark County 76% of Black males graduated compared to 67% for White males.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Further academic improvement has occurred in 2015.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Roughly 23% of all Blacks have bachelor's degrees.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In 1988, 21% of Whites had obtained a bachelor's degree versus 11% of Blacks.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In 2015, 23% of Blacks had obtained a bachelor's degree versus 36% of Whites.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Foreign born Blacks, 9% of the Black population, made even greater strides.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] They exceed native born Blacks by 10 percentage points.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] College Board, which runs the official college-level advanced placement (AP) programs in American high schools, have has received criticism in recent years that its curricula have focused too much on Euro-centric history.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In 2020, College Board reshaped some curricula among history-based courses to further reflect the African diaspora.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In 2021, College Board announced it would be piloting an AP African American Studies course between 2022 and 2024.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] The course officially launched in August 2024.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In June 2023, the Supreme Court ended race-based affirmative action at American colleges and universities.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In response, many of the nation's most prominent historically black colleges and universities (HBCUs) have reported a significant surge in applications and enrollment.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Slightly more than 250,000 African American students in the high school graduating class of 2025 took the Scholastic Aptitude Test (SAT) making up 13% of test takers.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] African American students had an average score of 904 which is lower than the national average of 1,209.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Asian American students had the highest average with 1,229.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] According to a 2025 study, African Americans have the highest average student debt.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] African Americans with bachelor's degrees owe an average of $52,726 in student loans.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Nearly 70% of African Americans took out a loan to fund their undergraduate education.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] African American women, in particular, carry the highest average student debt in the nation.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Historically black colleges and universities (HBCUs), which were founded when segregated institutions of higher learning did not admit African Americans, continue to thrive and educate students of all races today.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] There are 107 HBCUs representing three percent of the nation's colleges and universities with the majority established in the Southeast.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] HBCUs have been largely responsible for establishing and expanding the African American middle-class by providing more career opportunities for African Americans.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] The economic disparity between the races in the US has marginally improved since the end of slavery.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In 1863, two years prior to emancipation, Black people owned 0.5 percent of the national wealth, while in 2019 it is just over 1.5 percent.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Racial disparity in poverty rates has narrowed since the civil rights era, with the poverty rate among African Americans decreasing from 24.7% in 2004 to 18.8% in 2020, compared to 10.5% for all Americans.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Poverty is associated with higher rates of marital stress and dissolution, physical and mental health problems, disability, cognitive deficits, low educational attainment, and crime.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] African Americans have a long and diverse history of business ownership.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Although the first African American business is unknown, slaves captured from West Africa are believed to have established commercial enterprises as peddlers and skilled craftspeople as far back as the 17th century.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Washington became the most famous proponent of African American businesses.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] DuBois also commended business as a vehicle for African American advancement.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In 2002, African American-owned businesses accounted for 1.2 million of the US's 23 million businesses.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] As of 2011, African American-owned businesses account for approximately two million US businesses.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Black-owned businesses experienced the largest growth in number of businesses among minorities from 2002 to 2011.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Twenty-five percent of Blacks had white-collar occupations (management, professional, and related fields) in 2000, compared with 33.6% of Americans overall.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In 2001, over half of African American households of married couples earned $50,000 or more.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Although in the same year African Americans were over-represented among the nation's poor, this was directly related to the disproportionate percentage of African American families headed by single women; such families are collectively poorer, regardless of ethnicity.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In 2006, the median earnings of African American men was more than Black and non-Black American women overall, and in all educational levels.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] At the same time, among American men, income disparities were significant; the median income of African American men was approximately 76 cents for every dollar of their European American counterparts, although the gap narrowed somewhat with a rise in educational level.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Overall, the median earnings of African American men were 72 cents for every dollar earned of their Asian American counterparts, and $1.17 for every dollar earned by Hispanic men.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] On the other hand, by 2006, among American women with post-secondary education, African American women have made significant advances; the median income of African American women was more than those of their Asian-, European- and Hispanic American counterparts with at least some college education.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] The US public sector is the single most important source of employment for African Americans.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] During 2008–2010, 21.2% of all Black workers were public employees, compared with 16.3% of non-Black workers.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Both before and after the onset of the Great Recession, African Americans were 30% more likely than other workers to be employed in the public sector.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] The public sector is also a critical source of decent-paying jobs for Black Americans.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] For both men and women, the median wage earned by Black employees is significantly higher in the public sector than in other industries.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In 1999, the median income of African American families was $33,255 compared to $53,356 of European Americans.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In times of economic hardship for the nation, African Americans suffer disproportionately from job loss and underemployment, with the Black underclass being hardest hit.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] The phrase "last hired and first fired" is reflected in the Bureau of Labor Statistics unemployment figures.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Nationwide, the October 2008 unemployment rate for African Americans was 11.1%, while the nationwide rate was 6.5%.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In 2007, the average income for African Americans was approximately $34,000, compared to $55,000 for Whites.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] African Americans experience a higher rate of unemployment than the general population.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] The income gap between Black and White families is also significant.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In 2005, employed Blacks earned 65% of the wages of Whites, down from 82% in 1975.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] *The New York Times* reported in 2006 that in Queens, New York, the median income among African American families exceeded that of White families, which the newspaper attributed to the growth in the number of two-parent Black families.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] It noted that Queens was the only county with more than 65,000 residents where that was true.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In 2011, it was reported that 72% of Black babies were born to unwed mothers.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] The poverty rate among single-parent Black families was 39.5% in 2005, according to Walter E.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Williams, while it was 9.9% among married-couple Black families.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Among White families, the respective rates were 26.4% and 6% in poverty.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Collectively, African Americans are more involved in the American political process than other minority groups in the United States, indicated by the highest level of voter registration and participation in elections among these groups in 2004.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] African Americans also have the highest level of Congressional representation of any minority group in the US.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Homeownership in the US is the strongest indicator of financial stability and the primary asset most Americans use to generate wealth.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] African Americans continue to lag behind other racial groups in homeownership.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In the first quarter of 2021, 45.1% of African Americans owned their homes, compared to 65.3% of all Americans.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] The African American homeownership rate has remained relatively flat since the 1970s despite an increase in anti-discrimination housing laws and protections.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] The African American homeownership rate peaked in 2004 at 49.7%.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] The average White high school drop-out still has a slightly better chance of owning a home than the average African American college graduate usually due to unfavorable debt-to-income ratios or credit scores among most African American college graduates.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Since 2000, fast-growing housing costs in most cities have made it even more difficult for the US African American homeownership rate to significantly grow and reach over 50% for the first time in history.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] From 2000 to 2022, the median home price in the US grew 160%, outpacing average annual household income growth in that same period, which only grew about 30%.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] South Carolina is the state with the most African American homeownership, with about 55% of African Americans owning their own homes.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Black people, who make up 12% of the total U.S. population, make up 32% of all people experiencing homelessness, according to the data.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Since the mid 20th century, a large majority of African Americans support the Democratic Party.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In the 2024 Presidential election, 86% of African American voters supported Democrat Kamala Harris, while 13% supported Republican Donald Trump.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Although there is an African American lobby in foreign policy, it has not had the impact that African American organizations have had in domestic policy.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Many African Americans were excluded from electoral politics in the decades following the end of Reconstruction.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] The African American trend of voting for Democrats can be traced back to the 1930s during the Great Depression, when Franklin D.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Roosevelt's New Deal program provided economic relief to African Americans.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Roosevelt's New Deal coalition turned the Democratic Party into an organization of the working class and their liberal allies, regardless of region.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] The African American vote became even more solidly Democratic when Democratic presidents John F.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Johnson pushed for civil rights legislation during the 1960s.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In 1960, nearly a third of African Americans voted for Republican Richard Nixon.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Conservatism has been growing among African Americans, particularly since the 2020 Presidential election.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In the 2024 election, Trump secured a slightly larger share of the African American vote compared to his 2020 performance.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] "Lift Every Voice and Sing" is often referred to as the Black national anthem in the United States.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In 1919, the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) had dubbed it the "Negro national anthem" for its power in voicing a cry for liberation and affirmation for African-American people.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] The majority of African Americans are Protestant, many of whom follow the historically Black churches.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] The term Black church refers to churches which minister to predominantly African American congregations.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Black congregations were first established by freed slaves at the end of the 17th century, and later when slavery was abolished more African Americans were allowed to create a unique form of Christianity that was culturally influenced by African spiritual traditions.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] According to a 2007 survey, more than half of the African American population are part of the historically Black churches.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] The largest Protestant denomination among African Americans is the Baptists, distributed mainly in four denominations, the largest being the National Baptist Convention, USA and the National Baptist Convention of America.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] The second-largest is the Methodists, the largest organizations of which are the African Methodist Episcopal Church and the African Methodist Episcopal Zion Church.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Pentecostals are distributed among several different religious bodies, with the Church of God in Christ as the largest among them by far.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] About 16% of African American Christians are members of White Protestant communions; these denominations (which include the United Church of Christ) mostly have a 2–3% African American membership.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] There are also large numbers of Catholics, constituting 5% of the African American population.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Of the total number of Jehovah's Witnesses, 22% are Black.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Historically, between 15 and 30% of enslaved Africans brought to the Americas were Muslims, but most of these Africans were converted to Christianity during the era of American slavery.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Prominent members included activist Malcolm X and boxer Muhammad Ali.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] Malcolm X is considered the first person to start the movement among African Americans towards mainstream Islam, after he left the Nation and made the pilgrimage to Mecca.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] In 1975, Warith Deen Mohammed, the son of Elijah Muhammad took control of the Nation after his father's death and guided the majority of its members to orthodox Islam.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] African American Muslims constitute 20% of the total US Muslim population, the majority are Sunni or orthodox Muslims, some of these identify under the community of W.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] The Nation of Islam led by Louis Farrakhan has a membership ranging from 20,000 to 50,000 members.
[src:african-americans/african-americans-p02] There is also a small but growing group of African American Jews, making up less than 0.5% of African Americans or about 2% of the Jewish population in the United States.
